<P>In <A href="/wiki/Argument" title="Argument">logical argument</A> and <A href="/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title="Mathematical proof">mathematical proof</A>, the <B>therefore sign</B> (∴) is generally used before a <A href="/wiki/Logical_consequence" title="Logical consequence">logical consequence</A>, such as the conclusion of a <A href="/wiki/Syllogism" title="Syllogism">syllogism</A>. The symbol consists of three dots placed in an upright triangle and is read <I>therefore</I>. It is encoded at <SPAN class="nowrap"><SPAN class="monospaced" style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">U+2234</SPAN></SPAN> <SPAN style="font-size:125%">∴</SPAN> <SPAN class="smallcaps" style="font-variant: small-caps; font-size: smaller;">therefore</SPAN> (HTML <CODE>&#8756;</CODE> <B>·</B>  <CODE>&there4;</CODE>). For common use in Microsoft Office hold the ALT key and type "8756". While it is not generally used in formal writing, it is used in <A href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</A> and <A href="/wiki/Shorthand" title="Shorthand">shorthand</A>. It is complementary to <SPAN class="nowrap"><SPAN class="monospaced" style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">U+2235</SPAN></SPAN> <SPAN style="font-size:125%">∵</SPAN> <SPAN class="smallcaps" style="font-variant: small-caps; font-size: smaller;">because</SPAN> (HTML <CODE>&#8757;</CODE>).</P>
<P></P>

<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="History">History</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>According to <A href="/wiki/Florian_Cajori" title="Florian Cajori">Cajori</A>, <I>A History of Mathematical Notations,</I> <A href="/wiki/Johann_Rahn" title="Johann Rahn">Johann Rahn</A> used both the <I>therefore</I> and <I>because</I> signs to mean "therefore"; in the German edition of <I>Teutsche Algebra</I> (1659) the <I>therefore</I> sign was prevalent with the modern meaning, but in the 1668 English edition Rahn used the <I>because</I> sign more often to mean "therefore".<SUP id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-1">[1]</A></SUP> Other authors in the eighteenth century also used three dots in a triangle shape to signify "therefore," but as with Rahn, there wasn't much in the way of consistency as to how the triangle was oriented; <I>because</I> with its current meaning appears to have originated in the nineteenth century. In this century, the three-dot notation for therefore became very rare in continental Europe, but it remains popular in the British Isles.<SUP id="cite_ref-Cajori2011_2-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Cajori2011-2">[2]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Example_of_use">Example of use</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Example of use">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Used in a <A href="/wiki/Syllogism" title="Syllogism">syllogism</A>:</P>
<DL>
<DD>All gods are immortal.</DD>
<DD><A href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</A> is a god.</DD>
<DD>∴ Zeus is immortal.</DD>
</DL>
<DL>
<DD>x + 1 = 6</DD>
<DD>∴ x = 5</DD>
</DL>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Related_signs">Related signs</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Related signs">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tleft">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/220px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" width="220" height="156" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/330px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/440px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png 2x" data-file-width="1824" data-file-height="1290" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
A diploma from the Masonic <I><A href="/wiki/Grande_Loge_de_France" title="Grande Loge de France">Grande Loge de France</A></I> showing the symbol as a substitute for the dot of abbreviation.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The inverted form ∵, known as the <B>because sign</B>, is sometimes used as a <A href="/wiki/Shorthand" title="Shorthand">shorthand</A> form of "because". This is <A href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</A> character U+2235.</P>
<P>The <I>therefore</I> sign is sometimes used as a substitute for an <A href="/wiki/Asterism_(typography)" title="Asterism (typography)">asterism</A> ⁂.</P>
<P>In meteorology, the therefore sign is used to indicate moderate rain on a <A href="/wiki/Station_model" title="Station model">station model</A>; the asterism indicates moderate snow.</P>
<P>To denote <A href="/wiki/Logical_implication" class="mw-redirect" title="Logical implication">logical implication</A> or <A href="/wiki/Entailment" class="mw-redirect" title="Entailment">entailment</A>, various signs are used in <A href="/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title="Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</A>: →, ⇒, ⊃, ⊢, ⊨. These symbols are then part of a mathematical formula, and are not considered to be punctuation. In contrast, the therefore sign is traditionally used as a punctuation mark, and does not form part of a logical formula.<SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The graphically identical sign ∴ serves as a <A href="/wiki/Japanese_map_symbol" class="mw-redirect" title="Japanese map symbol">Japanese map symbol</A> on the maps of the <A href="/wiki/Geographical_Survey_Institute_of_Japan" class="mw-redirect" title="Geographical Survey Institute of Japan">Geographical Survey Institute of Japan</A>, indicating a tea plantation. On other maps the sign, often with thicker dots, is sometimes used to signal the presence of a national monument or <A href="/wiki/Ruins" title="Ruins">ruins</A>.</P>
<P>The character ஃ in the <A href="/wiki/Tamil_script" title="Tamil script">Tamil script</A> represents the <A href="/wiki/%C4%80ytam" class="mw-redirect" title="Āytam">āytam</A>, a special sound of the <A href="/wiki/Tamil_language" title="Tamil language">Tamil language</A>.</P>
<P>In <A href="/wiki/Masonic" class="mw-redirect" title="Masonic">Masonic</A> traditions the symbol is used for <A href="/wiki/Abbreviation" title="Abbreviation">abbreviation</A>, instead of the usual period. For example "R∴W∴ John Smith" is an abbreviation for "Right Worshipful John Smith" (the term Right Worshipful is an archaic title just as "Land Lord" is and indicates that Brother Smith is a Grand Lodge officer).<SUP id="cite_ref-Mackey_4-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Mackey-4">[4]</A></SUP></P>
<P>In <A href="/wiki/Norwegian_language" title="Norwegian language">Norwegian</A> and <A href="/wiki/Danish_language" title="Danish language">Danish</A>, a similar symbol is used as an explanatory symbol (<I>forklaringstegnet</I>). It can be typeset using the <A href="/wiki/Open_o" class="mw-redirect" title="Open o">open o</A> followed by a colon, thus: <B>ɔ:</B>. It is used for the meaning "namely", "id est", "scilicet" or similar<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[5]</A></SUP>.</P>

<P><B>Watchmen</B> were organized groups of men, usually authorized by a state, government, city, or society, to deter criminal activity and provide law enforcement as well as traditionally perform the services of <A href="/wiki/Public_security" title="Public security">public safety</A>, <A href="/wiki/Fire_lookout" title="Fire lookout">fire watch</A>, <A href="/wiki/Crime_prevention" title="Crime prevention">crime prevention</A>, <A href="/wiki/Detective" title="Detective">crime detection</A>, <A href="/wiki/Possession_of_stolen_goods" title="Possession of stolen goods">recovery of stolen goods</A>. Watchmen have existed since earliest recorded times in various guises throughout the world and were generally succeeded by the emergence of formally organized professional <A href="/wiki/Police" title="Police">policing</A>.</P>
<P></P>

<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Early_origins">Early origins</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Early origins">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>An early reference to a watch can be found in the <A href="/wiki/Bible" title="Bible">Bible</A> where the Prophet <A href="/wiki/Ezekiel" title="Ezekiel">Ezekiel</A> states that it was the duty of the watch to blow the horn and sound the alarm. (Ezekiel 33:1-6)</P>
<P>The existence of watchmen has also been found<SUP class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<I><A href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" title="Wikipedia:Citing sources"><SPAN title="Statement needs to be more specific about the content to which it refers. (November 2008)">specify</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP> in the <A href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman</A>, <A href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">Greek</A> and <A href="/wiki/Egyptian_Empire" class="mw-redirect" title="Egyptian Empire">Egyptian</A> Empires.<SUP class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<I><A href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><SPAN title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2008)">citation needed</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP></P>
<P>The <A href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</A> turned the role of a watchman into a profession by creating two organizations:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the <A href="/wiki/Praetorian_Guard" title="Praetorian Guard">Praetorian Guard</A> thus establishing a rank and file system with a Captain of the Guard.</LI>
<LI><A href="/wiki/Vigiles" title="Vigiles">Vigiles</A>, literally the watch.</LI>
</UL>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Watchmen_in_England">Watchmen in England</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Watchmen in England">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="The_Problem_of_the_Night">The Problem of the Night</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: The Problem of the Night">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>The streets in London were dark and had a shortage of and poor quality artificial light.<SUP id="cite_ref-:0_1-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:0-1">[1]</A></SUP> It had been recognized for centuries that the coming of darkness to the unlit streets of a town brought a heightened threat of danger, and that the night provided cover to the disorderly and immoral, and to those bent on <A href="/wiki/Robbery" title="Robbery">robbery</A> or <A href="/wiki/Burglary" title="Burglary">burglary</A> or who in other ways threatened physical harm to people in the streets and in their houses.<SUP id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-2">[2]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The anxieties that darkness gave rise to had been met by the formation of a night watch in the 13th century, and by the rules about who could use the streets after dark. These rules had for long been underpinned in London and other towns by the <A href="/wiki/Curfew" title="Curfew">curfew</A>, the time (announced by the ringing of a bell) at which the gates closed and the streets were cleared. Only people with good reason to be abroad could then travel through the City.<SUP id="cite_ref-:0_1-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:0-1">[1]</A></SUP> Anyone outside at night without reason or permission was suspicious and potentially criminal.<SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Allowances were usually made for people who had some social status on their side. Lord Fielding clearly expected to pass through London's streets untroubled at 1 am one night in 1641, and he quickly became piqued when his coach was stopped by the watch, shouting huffily that it was a 'disgrace' to stop someone of such high standing as he, and telling the <A href="/wiki/Constable" title="Constable">constable</A> in charge of the watch that he would box him on the ears if he did not let his coach carry on back to his house. 'It is impossible' to 'distinguish a lord from another man by the outside of a coach', the <A href="/wiki/Constable" title="Constable">constable</A> said later in his defence, 'especially at unreasonable times'.<SUP id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-4">[4]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Formation_of_Watchmen">Formation of Watchmen</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Formation of Watchmen">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>The <A href="/w/index.php?title=Ordinance_of_1233&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="Ordinance of 1233 (page does not exist)">Ordinance of 1233</A> required the appointment of watchmen.<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[5]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-6">[6]</A></SUP> The <A href="/wiki/Assize_of_Arms_of_1252" title="Assize of Arms of 1252">Assize of Arms of 1252</A>, which required the appointment of <A href="/wiki/Constables" class="mw-redirect" title="Constables">constables</A> to summon men to arms, quell <A href="/wiki/Breach_of_the_peace" title="Breach of the peace">breaches of the peace</A>, and to deliver offenders to the <A href="/wiki/Sheriff" title="Sheriff">sheriff</A>, is cited as one of the earliest creations of an English police force, as was the <A href="/wiki/Statute_of_Winchester" title="Statute of Winchester">Statute of Winchester</A> of 1285.<SUP id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-7">[7]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-8">[8]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-9">[9]</A></SUP> In 1252 a royal writ established a Watch and Ward with royal officers appointed as <A href="/wiki/Sheriff#England_and_Wales" title="Sheriff">Shire Reeves</A>:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>By order of the King of England the Winchester Act Mandating The Watch. Part Four and the King commandth that from henceforth all Watches be made as it hath been used in past times that was to wit from the day of Ascension unto the day of St. Michael<SUP id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-10">[10]</A></SUP> in every city by six men at every gate in every borough by twelve men in every town by six or four according to the number of inhabitants of the town. They shall keep the Watch all night from sun setting unto sun rising. And if any stranger do pass them by them he shall be arrested until morning and if no suspicion be found he shall go quit.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Later in 1279 <A href="/wiki/Edward_I_of_England" title="Edward I of England">King Edward I</A> formed a special guard of 20 <A href="/wiki/Sergeant_at_arms" class="mw-redirect" title="Sergeant at arms">sergeants at arms</A> who carried decorated battle maces as a badge of official office. By 1415 a watch was appointed to the <A href="/wiki/Parliament_of_England" title="Parliament of England">Parliament of England</A> and in 1485 <A href="/wiki/Henry_VII_of_England" title="Henry VII of England">King Henry VII</A> established a household watch that became known as the <A href="/wiki/Beefeaters" class="mw-redirect" title="Beefeaters">Beefeaters</A>.</P>
<P>After 1660 it seems that large numbers of men had avoided night-time service by paying for a substitute well before 1660. Substitution had become so common by the late 17th century that the night watch was virtually by then a fully paid force.<SUP id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-11">[11]</A></SUP></P>
<P>In October 1663 was promulgated an act of Common Council, known as 'Robinson's Act' from the name of the sitting lord mayor, that confirmed the duty of all householders in the City to take their turn at watching in order 'to keep the peace and apprehend night-walkers, malefactors and suspected persons'. For the most part the Common Council Act of 1663 reiterated the rules and obligations that had long existed. The number of watchmen required for each ward, it declared, was to be the number 'established by custom' – in fact, by an act of 1621. Even though it had been true before the civil war that the watch had already become a body of paid men, supported by what were in effect the fines collected from those with an obligation to serve, the Common Council did not acknowledge this in the confirming Act of 1663.<SUP id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-12">[12]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The act of 1663 confirmed that watch on its old foundations, and left its effective management to the ward authorities. The important matter to be arranged in the wards was who was going to serve and on what basis. How the money was to be collected to support a force of paid constables, and by whom, were crucial issues. The 1663 act left it to the ward beadle or a constable and it seems to have been increasingly the case that rather than individuals paying directly for a substitute, when their turn came to serve, the eligible householders were asked to contribute to a watch fund that supported hired man.<SUP id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-13">[13]</A></SUP></P>
<P>From the mid-1690s the City authorities made several attempts to replace Robinson's Act and establish the watch on a new footing. Though they did not say it directly, the overwhelming requirement was to get quotas adjusted to reflect the reality that the watch consisted of hired men rather than citizens doing their civic duty—the assumption upon which the 1663 act, and all previous acts, had been based.<SUP id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-14">[14]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The implications and consequences of changes in the watch were worked out in practice and in legislation in two stages between the Restoration and the middle decades of the 18th century. The first involved the gradual recognition that a paid (and full-time) watch needed to be differently constituted from one made up of unpaid citizens, a point accepted in practice in legislation passed by the Common Council in 1705, though it was not articulated in as direct a way.<SUP id="cite_ref-:4_15-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:4-15">[15]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The fact that the 1705 act called for watchmen to be strong and able-bodied men seems further confirmation that the watch was now expected to be made up of hired hands rather than every male house holder serving in turn. The act of 1705 laid out the new quotas of watchmen and the disposition of watch-stands agreed to each ward. To discourage the corruption that had been blamed for earlier under-manning, it forbade constables to collect and disturbs the money paid in for hired watchmen: that was now supposed to be the responsibility of the deputy and common councilmen of the ward.<SUP id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-16">[16]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The second stage was the recognition that watchmen could not be sustained without a major shift in the way local services were financed. This led to the City's acquisition of taxing power by means of an act of parliament in 1737 which changed the obligation to serve in person into an obligation to pay to support a force of salaried man.<SUP id="cite_ref-:4_15-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:4-15">[15]</A></SUP> Under the new act, the ward authorities also continued to hire their own watchmen and to make whatever local rules seemed appropriate—establishing, for example, the places in their wards where the watchmen would stand and the beats they would patrol. But the implementation of the new Watch Act did have the effect of imposing some uniformity on the watch over the whole City, making in the process some modest incursions into the local autonomy of the wards. One of the leading elements in the regime that emerged from the implementation of the new act was an agreement that every watchman would be paid the same amount and that the wages should be raised to thirteen pounds a year.<SUP id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-17">[17]</A></SUP></P>
<P>From 1485 to the 1820s, in the absence of a police force, it was the parish-based watchmen who were responsible for keeping order in London's streets.<SUP class="reference plainlinks nourlexpansion" id="ref_Ward"><A class="external autonumber" href="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watchman_(law_enforcement)#endnote_Ward">[1]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Duties">Duties</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Duties">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>Night watchmen patrolled the streets between 9 or 10 pm until sunrise, and were expected to examine all suspicious characters.<SUP id="cite_ref-:1_18-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:1-18">[18]</A></SUP> Such controls continued to be exercised in the late 17th century. Guarding the streets to prevent crime, to watch out for fires, and – despite the absence of a formal <A href="/wiki/Curfew" title="Curfew">curfew</A> – to ensure that suspicious and unauthorized people did not prowl around under cover of darkness was still the duty of night watch and the <A href="/wiki/Constable" title="Constable">constables</A> who were supposed to command them.<SUP id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-19">[19]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The principal task of the watch in 1660 and for long after continued to be the control of the streets at night imposing a form of moral or social <A href="/wiki/Curfew" title="Curfew">curfew</A> that aimed to prevent those without legitimate reason to be abroad from wandering the streets at night. That task was becoming increasingly difficult in the 17th century because of the growth of the population and variety of ways in which the social and cultural life was being transformed. The shape of the urban day was being altered after the Restoration by the development of <A href="/wiki/Retail_shop" class="mw-redirect" title="Retail shop">shops</A>, <A href="/wiki/Tavern" title="Tavern">taverns</A> and <A href="/wiki/Coffeehouse" title="Coffeehouse">coffee-houses</A>, <A href="/wiki/Theatre" title="Theatre">theatres</A>, the <A href="/wiki/Opera" title="Opera">opera</A> and other places of entertainment. All these placed remained open in the evening and extended their hours of business and pleasure into the night.<SUP id="cite_ref-:2_20-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:2-20">[20]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The watch was affected by this changing urban world since policing the night streets become more complicated when larger number of people were moving around. And what was frequently thought to be poor quality of the watchman—and in time, the lack of effective lighting—came commonly to be blamed when street crimes and night-time disorders seemed to be growing out of control.<SUP id="cite_ref-:2_20-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:2-20">[20]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Traditionally, householders served in the office of constable by appointment or rotation. During their year of office they performed their duties part-time alongside their normal employment. Similarly, householders were expected to serve by rotation on the nightly watch. From the late seventeenth century, however, many householders avoided these obligations by hiring deputies to serve in their place. As this practice increased, some men were able to make a living out of acting as deputy constables or as paid night watchmen. In the case of the watch, this procedure was formalized in many parts of London by the passage of "Watch Acts", which replaced householders' duty of service by a tax levied specifically for the purpose of hiring full-time watchmen. Some voluntary prosecution societies also hired men to patrol their areas.<SUP id="cite_ref-:1_18-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:1-18">[18]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Reputation">Reputation</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=6" title="Edit section: Reputation">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>While the societies for the reformation of manners showed there was a good deal of support for the effective policing of morality, they also suggested that the existing mechanisms of crime control were regarded by some as ineffective.<SUP id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-21">[21]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Constable Dogberry's men from <I><A href="/wiki/Much_Ado_About_Nothing" title="Much Ado About Nothing">Much Ado About Nothing</A></I> by Shakespeare would 'rather sleep than talk' may be dismissed as merely a dramatic device or a caricature, but successful dramatists nevertheless work with characters who strike a chord with their audience. A hundred years later such complaints were still commonplace. Daniel Defoe wrote four pamphlets and a broadsheet on the issue of street crime in which, among other things, he roundly attacked the efficacy of the watch and called for measures to ensure it 'be compos'd of stout, able-body'd Men, and of those a sufficient Number'.<SUP id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-22">[22]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Watchmen on roads leading to London had a reputation for clumsiness in the late 1580s. It was a temptation on cold winter nights to slip away early from watching stations to catch some sleep. <A href="/wiki/Constable" title="Constable">Constables</A> in charge sometimes let watches go home early. 'The late placing and early dischargering' of night-watches concerned <A href="/wiki/Common_Council_of_the_City_of_London" class="mw-redirect" title="Common Council of the City of London">Common Council</A> in 1609 and again 3 decades later when someone sent out to spy on watches reported that they 'break up longe before they ought'. 'The greatest parte of constables' broke up watches 'earlie in the morninge' at exactly the time 'when most danger' was 'feared' in the long night, leaving the dark streets to <A href="/wiki/Theft" title="Theft">thieves</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-23">[23]</A></SUP></P>
<P>We can imagine watchmen on chilly nights counting off the hours until sunrise. Alehouses offered some warmth, even after <A href="/wiki/Curfew" title="Curfew">curfew</A> bells told people to drink up. A group of watchmen sneaked into a 'vitlers' house one night in 1617 and stayed 'drinking and taking tobacco all night longe'.<SUP id="cite_ref-:3_24-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:3-24">[24]</A></SUP> Like other officers, watchmen could become the focus for trouble themselves, adding to the hullabaloo at night instead of ordering others to keep the noise down and go to bed. And as by day, there were more than a few crooked officers policing the streets at night, quite happy to turn a blind eye to trouble for a bribe. Watchman Edward Gardener was taken before the recorder with 'a common nightwalker' – Mary Taylor – in 1641 after he 'tooke 2s to lett' her 'escape' when he was escorting her to Bridewell late at night. Another watchman from over the river in Southwark took advantage of the tricky situation people suddenly found themselves in if they stumbled into the watch, 'demanding money [from them] for passing the watch'.<SUP id="cite_ref-:3_24-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-:3-24">[24]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Common complaint in the 1690s was that watchmen were inadequately armed. This was another aspect of the watch in the process of being transformed. The Common Council acts required watchmen to carry halberds essentially, a pike with an axe-blade attached—and some were still doing so in the late seventeenth century. But it seems clear that few did, because the <A href="/wiki/Halberd" title="Halberd">halberd</A> was no longer suitable for the work they were being called upon to do. It was more often observed that watchmen failed to carry them, and it is surely the case that the halberd was no longer a useful weapon for a watch that was supposed to be mobile. By the second quarter of the 18th century, watchmen were equipped with a staff, along with their lantern.<SUP id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-25">[25]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Watch_houses">Watch houses</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=7" title="Edit section: Watch houses">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810,_Norfolk_Crescent,_Bath.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg/220px-Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg/330px-Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg/440px-Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810%2C_Norfolk_Crescent%2C_Bath.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5401" data-file-height="3601" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Georgian_Watchman%27s_Box_c1810,_Norfolk_Crescent,_Bath.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
A rare and unusually fine Georgian Watchman's Box of about 1810. <A href="/wiki/Bath_(Somerset)" class="mw-redirect" title="Bath (Somerset)">Bath</A>, UK</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>Another step in the right direction was building 'watch howses' as the country lurched towards revolution after 1640. A City committee was asked to look into the question 'what watchhouses are necessary' and where 'for the safety of this cittye' in 1642. Workmen began building watch houses in strategic spots soon after. They provided assembly-points for watchmen to gather to hear orders for the night ahead, somewhere to shelter from 'extremitye of wind and weather', and holding-placed for suspects until morning when justices examined the night's catch. There were watch houses next to Temple Bar (1648), 'neere the Granaryes' by Bridewell (1648), 'neere Moregate' (1648), and next to St Paul's south door (1649). They were not big; the one on St. Paul's side was 'a small house or shed'. This was a time of experimentation, and people (including those in authority) were learning how to make best use of these new structures in their midst.<SUP id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-26">[26]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Policing_the_Night_Streets">Policing the Night Streets</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=8" title="Edit section: Policing the Night Streets">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>The watchmen patrolled the streets at night, calling out the hour, keeping a lookout for fires, checking that doors were locked and ensuring that drunks and other vagrants were delivered to the watch <A href="/wiki/Constable" title="Constable">constable</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-27">[27]</A></SUP> However, their low wages and the uncongenial nature of the job attracted a fairly low standard of person, and they acquired a possibly-exaggerated reputation for being old, ineffectual, feeble, drunk or asleep on the job.<SUP id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-28">[28]</A></SUP></P>
<P>London had a system of night policing in place before 1660, although it was improved over the next century through better lighting, administrations, finances, and better and more regular salaries. But the essential elements of the night-watch were performing completely by the middle of the seventeenth century.<SUP id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-29">[29]</A></SUP></P>
<P>During the 1820s, mounting crime levels and increasing political and industrial disorder prompted calls for reform, led by <A href="/wiki/Sir_Robert_Peel" class="mw-redirect" title="Sir Robert Peel">Sir Robert Peel</A>, which culminated in the demise of the watchmen and their replacement by a uniformed <A href="/wiki/Metropolitan_Police_Service" title="Metropolitan Police Service">metropolitan police force</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-30">[30]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-31">[31]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Watchmen_in_the_United_States_of_America">Watchmen in the United States of America</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=9" title="Edit section: Watchmen in the United States of America">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>The first form of societal protection in the <A href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</A> was based on practices developed in England. The City of <A href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</A> was the first settlement in the 13 colonies to establish a night watch in 1631.<A rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://www.nleomf.com/TheMemorial/Facts/impdates.htm">[2]</A> <A href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York</A> (then <A href="/wiki/New_Amsterdam" title="New Amsterdam">New Amsterdam</A>) and <A href="/wiki/Jamestown,_Virginia" title="Jamestown, Virginia">Jamestown</A> followed in 1658.</P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Watchmen_and_modern_police">Watchmen and modern police</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Watchman_(law_enforcement)&action=edit&section=10" title="Edit section: Watchmen and modern police">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>With the unification of laws and centralization of state power (<I>e.g.</I> the <A href="/w/index.php?title=Municipal_Police_Act&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="Municipal Police Act (page does not exist)">Municipal Police Act</A> of 1844 in <A href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</A>, <A href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</A>), such formations became increasingly incorporated into state-run police force (see <A href="/wiki/Metropolitan_police" title="Metropolitan police">metropolitan police</A> and <A href="/wiki/Municipal_police" title="Municipal police">municipal police</A>).</P>
<P>Watchmen still exist under Florida statutes and are recognised / given special dispensation in law.<SUP id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-32">[32]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-33">[33]</A></SUP></P>

<P>"<B>Photograph</B>" is a song by English musician <A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr" title="Ringo Starr">Ringo Starr</A> that was released as the <A href="/wiki/Lead_single" title="Lead single">lead single</A> from his 1973 album <I><A href="/wiki/Ringo_(album)" title="Ringo (album)">Ringo</A></I>. Starr co-wrote the song with <A href="/wiki/George_Harrison" title="George Harrison">George Harrison</A>, his former bandmate from <A href="/wiki/The_Beatles" title="The Beatles">the Beatles</A>. Although the two of them collaborated on other compositions, it is the only song officially credited to the pair. A signature tune for Starr as a solo artist, "Photograph" became an international hit, topping singles charts in the United States, Canada and Australia, and receiving <A href="/wiki/Gold_disc" class="mw-redirect" title="Gold disc">gold disc</A> certification for US sales of 1 million. Music critics have similarly received the song favourably; <A href="/wiki/Stephen_Thomas_Erlewine" title="Stephen Thomas Erlewine">Stephen Thomas Erlewine</A> of <A href="/wiki/AllMusic" title="AllMusic">AllMusic</A> considers it to be "among the very best post-Beatles songs by any of the Fab Four".<SUP id="cite_ref-Erlewine/AM_1-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Erlewine/AM-1">[1]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The lyrics are a reflection on lost love, whereby a photograph is the only reminder of the protagonists' shared past. Starr and Harrison began writing the song in the <A href="/wiki/South_of_France" class="mw-redirect" title="South of France">South of France</A> in 1971, during a period when Starr was focused on developing his acting career. They first recorded "Photograph" late the following year, along with the single's <A href="/wiki/B-side" class="mw-redirect" title="B-side">B-side</A>, "Down and Out", during sessions for Harrison's <I><A href="/wiki/Living_in_the_Material_World" title="Living in the Material World">Living in the Material World</A></I> album (1973). The officially released version was recorded in Los Angeles with producer <A href="/wiki/Richard_Perry" title="Richard Perry">Richard Perry</A>, and it incorporates aspects of <A href="/wiki/Phil_Spector" title="Phil Spector">Phil Spector</A>'s <A href="/wiki/Wall_of_Sound" title="Wall of Sound">Wall of Sound</A> through the presence of multiple drums and acoustic guitars, as well as an orchestra and a choir. Aside from Starr and Harrison, the musicians on the recording include <A href="/wiki/Nicky_Hopkins" title="Nicky Hopkins">Nicky Hopkins</A>, <A href="/wiki/Bobby_Keys" title="Bobby Keys">Bobby Keys</A>, <A href="/wiki/Jim_Keltner" title="Jim Keltner">Jim Keltner</A>, and Spector's musical arranger, <A href="/wiki/Jack_Nitzsche" title="Jack Nitzsche">Jack Nitzsche</A>. Starr made a promotional film for the single, shot at his and wife <A href="/wiki/Maureen_Starkey_Tigrett" title="Maureen Starkey Tigrett">Maureen Starkey</A>'s home, <A href="/wiki/Tittenhurst_Park" title="Tittenhurst Park">Tittenhurst Park</A>.</P>
<P>"Photograph" has appeared on Starr's compilation albums <I><A href="/wiki/Blast_from_Your_Past" title="Blast from Your Past">Blast from Your Past</A></I> (1975) and <I><A href="/wiki/Photograph:_The_Very_Best_of_Ringo_Starr" title="Photograph: The Very Best of Ringo Starr">Photograph: The Very Best of Ringo Starr</A></I> (2007), and live versions have featured on releases recorded with his <A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr_%26_His_All-Starr_Band" title="Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band">All-Starr Band</A> and with the Roundheads. In November 2002, a year after Harrison's death, Starr sang "Photograph" at the <A href="/wiki/Concert_for_George" title="Concert for George">Concert for George</A> – a performance that was an emotional highpoint of the event. <A href="/wiki/Engelbert_Humperdinck_(singer)" title="Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)">Engelbert Humperdinck</A>, <A href="/wiki/Camper_Van_Beethoven" title="Camper Van Beethoven">Camper Van Beethoven</A>, <A href="/wiki/Cilla_Black" title="Cilla Black">Cilla Black</A> and <A href="/wiki/Adam_Sandler" title="Adam Sandler">Adam Sandler</A> are among the artists who have covered the song.</P>
<P></P>
