<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Background_and_composition">Background and composition</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Background and composition">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Ex-<A href="/wiki/The_Beatles" title="The Beatles">Beatles</A> <A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr" title="Ringo Starr">Ringo Starr</A> and <A href="/wiki/George_Harrison" title="George Harrison">George Harrison</A> began writing "Photograph" on a luxury yacht in the <A href="/wiki/South_of_France" class="mw-redirect" title="South of France">South of France</A> in May 1971.<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_216_2-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_216-2">[2]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Badman_p_35_3-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Badman_p_35-3">[3]</A></SUP> Starr had hired a yacht, the <I>Marala</I>, for the duration of the <A href="/wiki/1971_Cannes_Film_Festival" title="1971 Cannes Film Festival">Cannes Film Festival</A>, after attending <A href="/wiki/Mick_Jagger" title="Mick Jagger">Mick Jagger</A>'s wedding in <A href="/wiki/St_Tropez" class="mw-redirect" title="St Tropez">St Tropez</A> with his wife, <A href="/wiki/Maureen_Starkey_Tigrett" title="Maureen Starkey Tigrett">Maureen Starkey</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Badman_p_35_3-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Badman_p_35-3">[3]</A></SUP> The Starkeys<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[nb 1]</A></SUP> were then joined in France by Harrison and the latter's wife, <A href="/wiki/Pattie_Boyd" title="Pattie Boyd">Pattie Boyd</A>, for the <A href="/wiki/1971_Monaco_Grand_Prix" title="1971 Monaco Grand Prix">Monaco Grand Prix</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-6">[5]</A></SUP> This period coincided with Starr's first success as a solo artist, with the Harrison-produced single "<A href="/wiki/It_Don%27t_Come_Easy" title="It Don't Come Easy">It Don't Come Easy</A>",<SUP id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-7">[6]</A></SUP> although he would continue to focus on his career as a film actor,<SUP id="cite_ref-Ingham_p_139_8-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Ingham_p_139-8">[7]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-9">[8]</A></SUP> beginning with a role in <I><A href="/wiki/Blindman" title="Blindman">Blindman</A></I> (1971).<SUP id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-10">[9]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-15">[nb 2]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Another guest on the <I>Marala</I> was <A href="/wiki/Cilla_Black" title="Cilla Black">Cilla Black</A>, singer and a friend to the Beatles since the 1960s, who recalls Starr and Harrison playing "Photograph" during an evening get-together, with "everyone on board" contributing ideas for the lyrics.<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_216_2-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_216-2">[2]</A></SUP> As with Starr's two singles over 1971–72, "It Don't Come Easy" and "<A href="/wiki/Back_Off_Boogaloo" title="Back Off Boogaloo">Back Off Boogaloo</A>",<SUP id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-16">[14]</A></SUP> Harrison helped write the melody,<SUP id="cite_ref-Woffinden_p_77_17-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Woffinden_p_77-17">[15]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Schaffner_p_161_18-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Schaffner_p_161-18">[16]</A></SUP> although "Photograph" would mark the first time that he was credited as a co-writer with Starr.<SUP id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-19">[17]</A></SUP> In her autobiography, <I>Step Inside Love</I>, Black says she had hoped to record the song for a single later in 1971, only to be told by Starr: "No, it's too bloody good for you. I'm having it myself."<SUP id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-20">[18]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The lyric to "Photograph" is centred around lost love,<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_244_21-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_244-21">[19]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Huntley_p_97_22-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Huntley_p_97-22">[20]</A></SUP> with the singer having only a single picture by which to remember his absent lover.<SUP id="cite_ref-Schaffner_p_161_18-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Schaffner_p_161-18">[16]</A></SUP> The eponymous photograph reminds him of their former happiness together, while also enforcing the reality that "you're not coming back any more".<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_55_23-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_55-23">[21]</A></SUP> Author Ian Inglis comments on the familiar subject matter in the conventions of pop songwriting, but identifies an "unusual" aspect in the lyrics' "absence of any hope that love might be rekindled".<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_55_23-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_55-23">[21]</A></SUP> Starr expresses resignation at what the future holds, in the lines "Now you're expecting me to live without you / But that's not something that I'm looking forward to".<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_55_23-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_55-23">[21]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Musically, the song is in the <A href="/wiki/Key_(music)" title="Key (music)">key</A> of <A href="/wiki/E_major" title="E major">E</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-24">[22]</A></SUP> with what Inglis terms an "easy melody" that allows for Starr's limitations as a singer.<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_55_23-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_55-23">[21]</A></SUP> Harrison's "distinctive composing style" is particularly evident, according to authors <A href="/wiki/Roy_Carr" title="Roy Carr">Roy Carr</A> and <A href="/wiki/Tony_Tyler" title="Tony Tyler">Tony Tyler</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Carr_&_Tyler_p_107_25-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Carr_&_Tyler_p_107-25">[23]</A></SUP> and Starr would later say of Harrison's role in their collaborations over this period: "I only know three <A href="/wiki/Chord_(music)" title="Chord (music)">chords</A> and he'd stick four more in, and they'd all think I was a genius."<SUP id="cite_ref-Rodriguez_p_261_26-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rodriguez_p_261-26">[24]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Recording">Recording</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Recording">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Starr continued to pursue his film career until the end of 1972,<SUP id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-27">[25]</A></SUP> while also participating in musical projects such as Harrison's <A href="/wiki/The_Concert_for_Bangladesh" title="The Concert for Bangladesh">Concert for Bangladesh</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-28">[26]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-32">[nb 3]</A></SUP> Late that year, Starr and Harrison recorded an early version of "Photograph" during the sessions for Harrison's <I><A href="/wiki/Living_in_the_Material_World" title="Living in the Material World">Living in the Material World</A></I> album (1973).<SUP id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-33">[30]</A></SUP> With Harrison producing,<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503_11-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503-11">[10]</A></SUP> this recording took place at either <A href="/wiki/Apple_Studio" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple Studio">Apple Studio</A> in central London, or Harrison's home studio, <A href="/wiki/FPSHOT" class="mw-redirect" title="FPSHOT">FPSHOT</A>, in Oxfordshire.<SUP id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-34">[31]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-35">[32]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Starr re-recorded the song in March 1973,<SUP id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-36">[33]</A></SUP> while working at <A href="/wiki/Sunset_Sound_Recorders" title="Sunset Sound Recorders">Sunset Sound Recorders</A> in Los Angeles on <I><A href="/wiki/Ringo_(album)" title="Ringo (album)">Ringo</A></I>, his first solo album in the <A href="/wiki/Rock_music" title="Rock music">rock</A><SUP id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-37">[34]</A></SUP> or contemporary <A href="/wiki/Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop</A> style.<SUP id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-38">[35]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-41">[nb 4]</A></SUP> He later described <I>Ringo</I> as an "accidental album", since it only came about because he was attending the <A href="/wiki/15th_Annual_Grammy_Awards" title="15th Annual Grammy Awards">Grammy Awards</A> in Nashville, where <I><A href="/wiki/The_Concert_for_Bangladesh_(album)" title="The Concert for Bangladesh (album)">The Concert for Bangladesh</A></I> won the <A href="/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Album_of_the_Year" title="Grammy Award for Album of the Year">Grammy for Best Album</A> of 1972.<SUP id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-42">[38]</A></SUP> Keen to find another activity to justify the flight to the US, Starr arranged to record with American producer <A href="/wiki/Richard_Perry" title="Richard Perry">Richard Perry</A> during the visit.<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501_43-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501-43">[39]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The recording engineer on "Photograph" was Bill Schnee,<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_306_12-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_306-12">[11]</A></SUP> and author Simon Leng suggests that Harrison helped "hew" the production.<SUP id="cite_ref-Leng_p_138_44-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Leng_p_138-44">[40]</A></SUP> Along with Starr (on drums) and Harrison (12-string acoustic guitar), the other musicians included <A href="/wiki/Nicky_Hopkins" title="Nicky Hopkins">Nicky Hopkins</A> (piano), <A href="/wiki/Klaus_Voormann" title="Klaus Voormann">Klaus Voormann</A> (bass) and <A href="/wiki/Jim_Keltner" title="Jim Keltner">Jim Keltner</A> (drums),<SUP id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-45">[41]</A></SUP> all of whom had participated in the sessions for <I>Material World</I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-46">[42]</A></SUP> In addition, <A href="/wiki/Vini_Poncia" title="Vini Poncia">Vini Poncia</A>, Starr's new songwriting partner,<SUP id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-47">[43]</A></SUP> and session musician Jimmy Calvert played acoustic rhythm guitar on the Los Angeles recording.<SUP id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-48">[44]</A></SUP></P>
<P><A href="/wiki/Overdubbing" title="Overdubbing">Overdubs</A> on the basic tracks recorded for <I>Ringo</I> took place from April to July 1973.<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501_43-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501-43">[39]</A></SUP> On "Photograph", the additional instrumentation included a saxophone solo by <A href="/wiki/Bobby_Keys" title="Bobby Keys">Bobby Keys</A><SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_241_49-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_241-49">[45]</A></SUP> and percussion played by one of Harrison's <A href="/wiki/Apple_Records" title="Apple Records">Apple Records</A> signings, brothers <A href="/wiki/Lon_%26_Derrek_Van_Eaton" title="Lon & Derrek Van Eaton">Lon and Derrek Van Eaton</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-50">[46]</A></SUP> Harrison added harmony and backing vocals,<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_306_12-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_306-12">[11]</A></SUP> supporting Starr's lead vocal part.<SUP id="cite_ref-Leng_p_139_51-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Leng_p_139-51">[47]</A></SUP></P>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:107px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg/105px-Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg" width="105" height="155" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg/158px-Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg/210px-Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1648" data-file-height="2426" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Jack_Nitzsche_1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
Musical arranger <A href="/wiki/Jack_Nitzsche" title="Jack Nitzsche">Jack Nitzsche</A> helped give the recording a sound typical of <A href="/wiki/Phil_Spector" title="Phil Spector">Phil Spector</A>'s hit productions from the 1960s; photo by Brian Ashley White</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P><A href="/wiki/Jack_Nitzsche" title="Jack Nitzsche">Jack Nitzsche</A>, <A href="/wiki/Phil_Spector" title="Phil Spector">Phil Spector</A>'s musical arranger for much of the 1960s,<SUP id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-52">[48]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-53">[49]</A></SUP> provided the song's string and choral arrangements, which were overdubbed at Burbank Studios on 29 June.<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503_11-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503-11">[10]</A></SUP> Aside from Nitzsche's contributions, the recording incorporates aspects of Spector's <A href="/wiki/Wall_of_Sound" title="Wall of Sound">Wall of Sound</A> production<SUP id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-54">[50]</A></SUP> through the use of multiple rhythm guitars and drums, and prominent percussion such as <A href="/wiki/Castanets" title="Castanets">castanets</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_307_55-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_307-55">[51]</A></SUP> Leng draws parallels between the "resonant arrangement" on "Photograph" and the production that Harrison adopted for <A href="/wiki/Ravi_Shankar" title="Ravi Shankar">Ravi Shankar</A>'s song "<A href="/wiki/I_Am_Missing_You" title="I Am Missing You">I Am Missing You</A>",<SUP id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-56">[52]</A></SUP> an April 1973 recording that also featured Starr.<SUP id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-57">[53]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN id=".22Down_and_Out.22"></SPAN><SPAN class="mw-headline" id=""Down_and_Out"">"Down and Out"</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: "Down and Out"">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>With "Photograph" selected as the album's <A href="/wiki/Lead_single" title="Lead single">lead single</A>, Starr chose "Down and Out", a song written by him alone, for the <A href="/wiki/B-side" class="mw-redirect" title="B-side">B-side</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_244_21-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_244-21">[19]</A></SUP> Starr recorded the song in England, backed by Harrison, pianist <A href="/wiki/Gary_Wright" title="Gary Wright">Gary Wright</A> and Voormann.<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_303_58-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_303-58">[54]</A></SUP> The Harrison-produced session most likely took place in 1972, according to authors Chip Madinger and Mark Easter, during the same period as Starr and Harrison's first attempt at recording "Photograph".<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_507_59-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_507-59">[55]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-63">[nb 5]</A></SUP></P>
<P>A <A href="/wiki/Twelve-bar_blues" title="Twelve-bar blues">twelve-bar blues</A> with what Starr biographer <A href="/wiki/Alan_Clayson" title="Alan Clayson">Alan Clayson</A> describes as "perfunctory" lyrics, the recording features solos from Harrison, on <A href="/wiki/Slide_guitar" title="Slide guitar">slide guitar</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_244_21-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_244-21">[19]</A></SUP> and Wright.<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_507_59-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_507-59">[55]</A></SUP> Perry subsequently added a horn section, resulting in him being credited as co-producer on the track.<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_303_58-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_303-58">[54]</A></SUP> Carr and Tyler dismiss "Down and Out" with the description: "a very mundane throwaway tune only saved from extinction by the professional arrangement and by Harrison's distinctive slide-guitar solo".<SUP id="cite_ref-Carr_&_Tyler_p_107_25-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Carr_&_Tyler_p_107-25">[23]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Release">Release</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Release">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Apple Records released "Photograph", backed by "Down and Out", on 24 September 1973 in America, and on 19 October in Britain.<SUP id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-64">[59]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-66">[nb 6]</A></SUP> Starr made a promotional film for "Photograph", in which he mimed to the song while walking through the grounds of <A href="/wiki/Tittenhurst_Park" title="Tittenhurst Park">Tittenhurst Park</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Badman_p_108_67-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Badman_p_108-67">[61]</A></SUP> the <A href="/wiki/Berkshire" title="Berkshire">Berkshire</A> estate that he had recently purchased from former bandmate <A href="/wiki/John_Lennon" title="John Lennon">John Lennon</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-68">[62]</A></SUP> To circumvent the <A href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</A>'s ban on <A href="/wiki/Lip-synching_in_music" class="mw-redirect" title="Lip-synching in music">lip-synching</A>, Starr placed his hand over his mouth for part of the song,<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503_11-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503-11">[10]</A></SUP> thereby making it impossible to tell whether he was singing or merely miming.<SUP id="cite_ref-Badman_p_108_67-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Badman_p_108-67">[61]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-69">[nb 7]</A></SUP> The single's picture sleeve consisted of a photo by <A href="/wiki/Barry_Feinstein" title="Barry Feinstein">Barry Feinstein</A> that showed Starr's head poking through a large star made of silver foil.<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_302_70-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_302-70">[63]</A></SUP> The same image, which author <A href="/wiki/Bruce_Spizer" title="Bruce Spizer">Bruce Spizer</A> terms "the Ringo starfish", appeared on the single's face labels and on those of the <I>Ringo</I> album.<SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_302_70-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_302-70">[63]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The album's release followed in November 1973,<SUP id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-71">[64]</A></SUP> with "Photograph" appearing as the third track, preceding another Harrison contribution, "<A href="/wiki/Sunshine_Life_for_Me_(Sail_Away_Raymond)" title="Sunshine Life for Me (Sail Away Raymond)">Sunshine Life for Me (Sail Away Raymond)</A>".<SUP id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-72">[65]</A></SUP> Opposite the printed lyrics for "Photograph" inside the album booklet, a <A href="/wiki/Lithography" title="Lithography">lithograph</A> by Voormann depicted a framed picture on a shelf or desktop, in which Starr looks dejectedly at a framed picture of a woman.<SUP id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-73">[66]</A></SUP> In his personal life at this point, the album's arrival coincided with the failure of Starr's marriage, partly as a result of Harrison and Maureen conducting an affair.<SUP id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-74">[67]</A></SUP> While the friendship between the two former bandmates soon recovered,<SUP id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-75">[68]</A></SUP> Starr and Harrison would not officially write another song together after "Photograph".<SUP id="cite_ref-Rodriguez_p_157_76-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rodriguez_p_157-76">[69]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Noting the context in which Starr's song of "beautiful sadness" was released in the United States, Clayson describes "Photograph" as having been a popular request on radio playlists "for a nation still awaiting the return of many of its sons from <A href="/wiki/Vietnam_War" title="Vietnam War">Vietnam</A>, following the <A href="/wiki/Agreement_on_Ending_the_War_and_Restoring_Peace_in_Vietnam" class="mw-redirect" title="Agreement on Ending the War and Restoring Peace in Vietnam">January cease-fire</A>".<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_244_21-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_244-21">[19]</A></SUP> Rodriguez comments on the precipitous timing of the single, which "capitaliz[ed] on the year's nostalgia craze",<SUP id="cite_ref-Rodriguez_p_261_26-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rodriguez_p_261-26">[24]</A></SUP> while news of Starr recording with each of his former bandmates during the <I>Ringo</I> sessions provided further impetus.<SUP id="cite_ref-Schaffner_p_161_18-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Schaffner_p_161-18">[16]</A></SUP> In late November, the single topped America's <A href="/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100" title="Billboard Hot 100"><I>Billboard</I> Hot 100</A> for one week,<SUP id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-77">[70]</A></SUP> Starr's first number 1 hit on that chart as a solo artist<SUP id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-78">[71]</A></SUP> and Harrison's third there as a composer since <A href="/wiki/Break-up_of_the_Beatles" title="Break-up of the Beatles">the Beatles' break-up</A> in 1970.<SUP id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-79">[72]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-80">[73]</A></SUP> "Photograph" was also number 1 in Canada and Australia, while in Britain it peaked at number 8.<SUP id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-81">[74]</A></SUP> In Rodriguez's words, the single "did a good job of setting the table" for <I>Ringo</I>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Rodriguez_p_261_26-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rodriguez_p_261-26">[24]</A></SUP> which also enjoyed considerable commercial success.<SUP id="cite_ref-Schaffner_p_161_18-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Schaffner_p_161-18">[16]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501_43-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_501-43">[39]</A></SUP> On 28 December 1973, "Photograph" was certified <A href="/wiki/Music_recording_sales_certification" title="Music recording sales certification">gold</A> by the <A href="/wiki/Recording_Industry_Association_of_America" title="Recording Industry Association of America">Recording Industry Association of America</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-riaa_82-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-riaa-82">[75]</A></SUP> signifying US sales of 1 million<SUP id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-83">[76]</A></SUP> – Starr's second such award, after "It Don't Come Easy".<SUP id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-84">[77]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Reception">Reception</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Reception">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>On release, Ben Gerson of <I><A href="/wiki/Rolling_Stone" title="Rolling Stone">Rolling Stone</A></I> highlighted "Photograph" as one of the album's "three most wonderful songs", along with the Lennon-composed "<A href="/wiki/I%27m_the_Greatest" title="I'm the Greatest">I'm the Greatest</A>" and the Harrison–<A href="/wiki/Mal_Evans" title="Mal Evans">Mal Evans</A> collaboration "<A href="/wiki/You_and_Me_(Babe)" title="You and Me (Babe)">You and Me (Babe)</A>".<SUP id="cite_ref-Gerson/RS_85-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Gerson/RS-85">[78]</A></SUP> Gerson noted how the song's intro provided an effective "pull on the listener" and wrote that, while the lyrics had a sorrowful quality, "the effect is warming".<SUP id="cite_ref-Gerson/RS_85-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Gerson/RS-85">[78]</A></SUP> <I><A href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</A></I><SPAN class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</SPAN>s album reviewer praised Perry's "stunning production" on "the best Ringo album ever", adding: "We all know already that 'Photograph' has got to be a No. 1 single this month, right?"<SUP id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-86">[79]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Although less impressed with <I>Ringo</I>, Alan Betrock wrote in <I><A href="/wiki/Phonograph_Record_(magazine)" title="Phonograph Record (magazine)">Phonograph Record</A></I>: "It's also clear when you reach 'Photograph' that Side One is the undisputed champ of the album. Jack Nitzsche has thrown in a lot of <I>his</I> past influences here, including the Famous School of Phil Spector castanets, lesson No. 2."<SUP id="cite_ref-Betrock/PhonRec_87-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Betrock/PhonRec-87">[80]</A></SUP> Betrock concluded of the song: "'Photograph' is one of those rare pop records that grows stronger with each play, and will be covered and revived for years to come (I'll lay you 50-1 it appears on the next <A href="/wiki/Andy_Williams" title="Andy Williams">Andy Williams</A> album)."<SUP id="cite_ref-Betrock/PhonRec_87-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Betrock/PhonRec-87">[80]</A></SUP></P>
<P><A href="/wiki/Stephen_Thomas_Erlewine" title="Stephen Thomas Erlewine">Stephen Thomas Erlewine</A> of <A href="/wiki/AllMusic" title="AllMusic">AllMusic</A> considers "Photograph" a "gorgeous collaboration" between Starr and Harrison, a track that "ranks ... among the very best post-Beatles songs by any of the Fab Four".<SUP id="cite_ref-Erlewine/AM_1-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Erlewine/AM-1">[1]</A></SUP> Robert Rodriguez describes it as "an elegantly produced ballad" and Starr's "signature tune as a solo artist".<SUP id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-88">[81]</A></SUP> Rodriguez continues: "The ersatz Wall of Sound somehow managed not to swamp the lead vocal and Harrison harmony, while embodying the best qualities of the Beatles' singles: hummable and familiar, yet fresh and enduring."<SUP id="cite_ref-Rodriguez_p_143_89-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rodriguez_p_143-89">[82]</A></SUP> In his 1977 book <I>The Beatles Forever</I>, Nicholas Schaffner wrote of how the song's "grand, sweeping arrangement" was reminiscent of Harrison's "own recent cosmic productions".<SUP id="cite_ref-Schaffner_p_161_18-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Schaffner_p_161-18">[16]</A></SUP> Author Elliot Huntley similarly acknowledges the extent of Harrison's influence on this and other tracks on <I>Ringo</I> while rueing that "Photograph" marks the only formal co-composition by the two ex-Beatles.<SUP id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-90">[83]</A></SUP> Huntley describes the song as the album's "stand-out track" and "by a country mile, the commercial high-point" for Starr as a songwriter.<SUP id="cite_ref-Huntley_p_97_22-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Huntley_p_97-22">[20]</A></SUP> Former <I><A href="/wiki/Mojo_(magazine)" title="Mojo (magazine)">Mojo</A></I> editor <A href="/wiki/Mat_Snow" title="Mat Snow">Mat Snow</A> recognises it as "perhaps the single best song of [Starr's] career" and the "emotional heart" of the album.<SUP id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-91">[84]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Re-releases_and_live_versions">Re-releases and live versions</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=6" title="Edit section: Re-releases and live versions">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>The song provided the title to Starr's 2007 career-spanning compilation <I><A href="/wiki/Photograph:_The_Very_Best_of_Ringo_Starr" title="Photograph: The Very Best of Ringo Starr">Photograph: The Very Best of Ringo Starr</A></I>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Erlewine/AM_1-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Erlewine/AM-1">[1]</A></SUP> having earlier appeared on <I><A href="/wiki/Blast_from_Your_Past" title="Blast from Your Past">Blast from Your Past</A></I> (1975), a greatest-hits collection covering his years on Apple Records.<SUP id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-92">[85]</A></SUP> For the 1991 CD reissue of <I>Ringo</I>, the album was expanded through the inclusion of three bonus tracks,<SUP id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-93">[86]</A></SUP> the last of which was the long-unavailable "Down and Out".<SUP id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-94">[87]</A></SUP> In 2009, "Photograph" was featured in the <A href="/wiki/Judd_Apatow" title="Judd Apatow">Judd Apatow</A>-directed film <I><A href="/wiki/Funny_People" title="Funny People">Funny People</A></I><SUP id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-95">[88]</A></SUP> and appeared on the <A href="/wiki/Funny_People#Soundtrack" title="Funny People">accompanying soundtrack album</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-96">[89]</A></SUP></P>
<DIV class="thumb tleft">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:167px;"><A href="/wiki/File:20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg/165px-20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg" width="165" height="123" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg/248px-20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg/330px-20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2542" data-file-height="1900" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:20110626_102_All-Starr-Band-in-Paris_Ringo-Starr_WP_cropped.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
Starr performing with his <A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr_%26_His_All-Starr_Band" title="Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band">All-Starr Band</A> in 2011</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>Following his return to touring in July 1989<SUP id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-97">[90]</A></SUP> – the first tour for Starr since the Beatles quit performing live in 1966<SUP id="cite_ref-Sandall/Q_98-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Sandall/Q-98">[91]</A></SUP> – he has played "Photograph" regularly with the various incarnations of his <A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr_%26_His_All-Starr_Band" title="Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band">All-Starr Band</A>. Eschewing his drum kit for the role of lead singer,<SUP id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-99">[92]</A></SUP> Starr often closed his shows with the song (before returning for an <A href="/wiki/Encore_(concert)" class="mw-redirect" title="Encore (concert)">encore</A>) during tours he made between 1989 and 2000.<SUP id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-100">[93]</A></SUP> A live version appeared on the album and video <I><A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr_and_His_All-Starr_Band" title="Ringo Starr and His All-Starr Band">Ringo Starr and His All-Starr Band</A></I> (1990);<SUP id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-101">[94]</A></SUP> recorded at the <A href="/wiki/Greek_Theatre_(Los_Angeles)" title="Greek Theatre (Los Angeles)">Greek Theatre</A>, Los Angeles, on 3 September 1989,<SUP id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-102">[95]</A></SUP> it features the original All-Starr line-up of Starr, <A href="/wiki/Billy_Preston" title="Billy Preston">Billy Preston</A>, Jim Keltner, <A href="/wiki/Rick_Danko" title="Rick Danko">Rick Danko</A>, <A href="/wiki/Levon_Helm" title="Levon Helm">Levon Helm</A>, <A href="/wiki/Dr._John" title="Dr. John">Dr. John</A>, <A href="/wiki/Joe_Walsh" title="Joe Walsh">Joe Walsh</A>, <A href="/wiki/Nils_Lofgren" title="Nils Lofgren">Nils Lofgren</A> and <A href="/wiki/Clarence_Clemons" title="Clarence Clemons">Clarence Clemons</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-103">[96]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Starr also included the song in his performances on the television shows <I><A href="/wiki/VH1_Storytellers" title="VH1 Storytellers">VH1 Storytellers</A></I>, in May 1998,<SUP id="cite_ref-Harry_p_186_104-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Harry_p_186-104">[97]</A></SUP> and <A href="/wiki/PBS" title="PBS">PBS</A>'s <I><A href="/wiki/Soundstage_(TV_series)" title="Soundstage (TV series)">Soundstage</A></I>, in August 2005.<SUP id="cite_ref-Erlewine/Soundstage_105-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Erlewine/Soundstage-105">[98]</A></SUP> Featuring backing from the Roundheads – a band led by his latter-day producer <A href="/wiki/Mark_Hudson_(musician)" title="Mark Hudson (musician)">Mark Hudson</A> – these recordings were issued on Starr's releases <I><A href="/wiki/VH1_Storytellers_(Ringo_Starr_album)" title="VH1 Storytellers (Ringo Starr album)">VH1 Storytellers</A></I> (1998)<SUP id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-106">[99]</A></SUP> and <I><A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr:_Live_at_Soundstage" title="Ringo Starr: Live at Soundstage">Ringo Starr: Live at Soundstage</A></I> (2007), respectively.<SUP id="cite_ref-Erlewine/Soundstage_105-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Erlewine/Soundstage-105">[98]</A></SUP> Further versions with his All-Starr Band have appeared on the albums <I><A href="/wiki/King_Biscuit_Flower_Hour_Presents_Ringo_%26_His_New_All-Starr_Band" title="King Biscuit Flower Hour Presents Ringo & His New All-Starr Band">King Biscuit Flower Hour Presents Ringo & His New All-Starr Band</A></I> (2002),<SUP id="cite_ref-Harry_p_186_104-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Harry_p_186-104">[97]</A></SUP> <I><A href="/wiki/Ringo_Starr_%26_His_All_Starr_Band_Live_2006" title="Ringo Starr & His All Starr Band Live 2006">Ringo Starr & His All Starr Band Live 2006</A></I> (2008)<SUP id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-107">[100]</A></SUP> and <I><A href="/wiki/Live_at_the_Greek_Theatre_2008" title="Live at the Greek Theatre 2008">Live at the Greek Theatre 2008</A></I> (2010), the latter with Gary Wright among the revised line-up.<SUP id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-108">[101]</A></SUP> Starr re-recorded the song with the American band <A href="/wiki/Vandaveer" title="Vandaveer">Vandaveer</A> for his 2017 album <I><A href="/wiki/Give_More_Love" title="Give More Love">Give More Love</A></I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Billboard_109-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Billboard-109">[102]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Performance_at_the_Concert_for_George">Performance at the Concert for George</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=7" title="Edit section: Performance at the Concert for George">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>On 29 November 2002, Starr performed "Photograph" at the <A href="/wiki/Concert_for_George" title="Concert for George">Concert for George</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-110">[103]</A></SUP> held at London's <A href="/wiki/Royal_Albert_Hall" title="Royal Albert Hall">Royal Albert Hall</A> to mark the first anniversary of Harrison's death.<SUP id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-111">[104]</A></SUP> According to the Concert for George website: "Ringo Starr caught everyone with a tear in their eye with a rendition of 'Photograph', a composition he wrote with George, which seemed to sum up how everyone felt."<SUP id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-112">[105]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Starr's appearance came towards the end of the concert, and Inglis writes that his arrival was "given an extra poignancy by his choice of song".<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_126_113-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_126-113">[106]</A></SUP> In his preamble to the audience, Starr stated, "I loved George, George loved me",<SUP id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-114">[107]</A></SUP> before mentioning that "Photograph" had taken on a new meaning with the passing of Harrison.<SUP id="cite_ref-Inglis_p_126_113-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Inglis_p_126-113">[106]</A></SUP> This performance – with a large band that included <A href="/wiki/Jeff_Lynne" title="Jeff Lynne">Jeff Lynne</A>, <A href="/wiki/Eric_Clapton" title="Eric Clapton">Eric Clapton</A>, <A href="/wiki/Dhani_Harrison" title="Dhani Harrison">Dhani Harrison</A>, Preston, Keltner and saxophonist <A href="/wiki/Jim_Horn" title="Jim Horn">Jim Horn</A> – was issued on the <I><A href="/wiki/Concert_for_George_(album)" title="Concert for George (album)">Concert for George</A></I> album (2003)<SUP id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-115">[108]</A></SUP> and appears in <A href="/wiki/David_Leland" title="David Leland">David Leland</A>'s <A href="/wiki/Concert_for_George_(film)" title="Concert for George (film)">documentary film of the event</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-116">[109]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-117">[110]</A></SUP> In a July 2003 interview, Starr discussed his recently released tribute song to Harrison, "<A href="/wiki/Never_Without_You" title="Never Without You">Never Without You</A>", while acknowledging that he remained closest to Harrison out of all the former Beatles following the band's break-up.<SUP id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-118">[111]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Performance_at_the_2014_Grammy_Awards">Performance at the 2014 Grammy Awards</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=8" title="Edit section: Performance at the 2014 Grammy Awards">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>Starr sang "Photograph" at the <A href="/wiki/56th_Annual_Grammy_Awards" title="56th Annual Grammy Awards">56th Annual Grammy Awards</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-UCR/Grammys_119-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-UCR/Grammys-119">[112]</A></SUP> during which he and <A href="/wiki/Paul_McCartney" title="Paul McCartney">Paul McCartney</A>, as the two surviving ex-Beatles, were honoured with the <A href="/wiki/National_Academy_of_Recording_Arts_and_Sciences" class="mw-redirect" title="National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences">Recording Academy</A>'s <A href="/wiki/Grammy_Lifetime_Achievement_Award" title="Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award">Lifetime Achievement Award</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Contact/Grammys_120-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Contact/Grammys-120">[113]</A></SUP> The event took place at the <A href="/wiki/Staples_Center" title="Staples Center">Staples Center</A> in Los Angeles on 26 January 2014.<SUP id="cite_ref-Guardian/Grammys_121-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Guardian/Grammys-121">[114]</A></SUP> <I>Rolling Stone</I> reported on Starr's performance of the song: "Backed by a massive full band, he bounced around the stage while old black-and-white photographs showed on a big screen behind him."<SUP id="cite_ref-RS/Grammys_122-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RS/Grammys-122">[115]</A></SUP> The accompanying images were taken from Starr's recently published book;<SUP id="cite_ref-UCR/Grammys_119-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-UCR/Grammys-119">[112]</A></SUP> also titled <I>Photograph</I>, it consists of photos from his personal collection, dating back to the 1950s and '60s.<SUP id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-123">[116]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Cover_versions_and_references">Cover versions and references</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Photograph_(Ringo_Starr_song)&action=edit&section=9" title="Edit section: Cover versions and references">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P><A href="/wiki/Engelbert_Humperdinck_(singer)" title="Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)">Engelbert Humperdinck</A> and <A href="/wiki/The_Ray_Conniff_Singers" class="mw-redirect" title="The Ray Conniff Singers">the Ray Conniff Singers</A> each released recordings of the song in 1974.<SUP id="cite_ref-124" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-124">[117]</A></SUP> The following year, London-based recording engineer <A href="/wiki/David_Hentschel" title="David Hentschel">David Hentschel</A> covered "Photograph", along with all the other tracks on <I>Ringo</I>,<SUP id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-125">[118]</A></SUP> for his album <I>Sta*rtling Music</I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-Woff/RingO_126-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Woff/RingO-126">[119]</A></SUP> The latter, an experimental work featuring Hentschel on <A href="/wiki/ARP_synthesizer" class="mw-redirect" title="ARP synthesizer">ARP synthesizer</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-127">[120]</A></SUP> was the first release on Starr's short-lived record label, <A href="/wiki/Ring_O%27_Records" title="Ring O' Records">Ring O' Records</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-128">[121]</A></SUP></P>
<P>A cover version of the song by American <A href="/wiki/Alternative_rock" title="Alternative rock">alt rock</A> band <A href="/wiki/Camper_Van_Beethoven" title="Camper Van Beethoven">Camper Van Beethoven</A> appeared on their 1993 rarities compilation <I><A href="/wiki/Camper_Vantiquities" title="Camper Vantiquities">Camper Vantiquities</A></I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-129">[122]</A></SUP> Canadian band <A href="/wiki/Sloan_(band)" title="Sloan (band)">Sloan</A> made mention of "Photograph" in their 1996 single "<A href="/wiki/The_Lines_You_Amend" title="The Lines You Amend">The Lines You Amend</A>", the lyrics of which refer to a song "<I>... about photographs / Sung by Ringo Starr / Especially in the chorus part / You always said, 'Now don't you start'.</I>"<SUP id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-130">[123]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Cilla Black eventually recorded "Photograph", for her 2003 album <I><A href="/wiki/Beginnings:_Greatest_Hits_%26_New_Songs" title="Beginnings: Greatest Hits & New Songs">Beginnings: Greatest Hits & New Songs</A></I> – a version that "she jumps into head first at her most soulful", according to music critic Bruce Eder.<SUP id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-131">[124]</A></SUP> While Starr's original recording appeared on the soundtrack to <I>Funny People</I>, a cover by the film's leading actor, <A href="/wiki/Adam_Sandler" title="Adam Sandler">Adam Sandler</A>, is available as an <A href="/wiki/ITunes" title="ITunes">iTunes</A> bonus track with the album.<SUP id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-132">[125]</A></SUP></P>

<DIV class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">
<OL class="references">
<LI id="cite_note-5"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-5"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">Starr's real name is Richard Starkey.<SUP id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-4">[4]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-15"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-15"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">Some sources claim that "Photograph" originated in Almeria, Spain, where Starr was filming <I>Blindman</I>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503_11-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Madinger_&_Easter_p_503-11">[10]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Spizer_p_306_12-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Spizer_p_306-12">[11]</A></SUP> yet his role in that film was only confirmed at the end of the Cannes Film Festival.<SUP id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-13">[12]</A></SUP> According to entries in Keith Badman's book <I>The Beatles Diary Volume 2</I>, Starr joined the production in Rome on 17 June before carrying out location filming in Almeria through July.<SUP id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-14">[13]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-32"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-32"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">Starr and Harrison both contributed to 1972 albums by <A href="/wiki/Bobby_Keys" title="Bobby Keys">Bobby Keys</A>, <A href="/wiki/Harry_Nilsson" title="Harry Nilsson">Harry Nilsson</A> and <A href="/wiki/Lon_%26_Derrek_Van_Eaton" title="Lon & Derrek Van Eaton">Lon & Derrek Van Eaton</A>,<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_240_29-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_240-29">[27]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-30">[28]</A></SUP> in addition to participating in a session for a <A href="/wiki/I%27ll_Still_Love_You#Cilla_Black" title="I'll Still Love You">proposed Cilla Black single</A> in August 1972.<SUP id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-31">[29]</A></SUP> Author <A href="/wiki/Alan_Clayson" title="Alan Clayson">Alan Clayson</A> refers to Harrison and Starr as "the <A href="/wiki/Tweedledum_and_Tweedledee" title="Tweedledum and Tweedledee">Tweedledum and Tweedledee</A> of such occasions", due to their many sessions together during the early 1970s.<SUP id="cite_ref-Clayson_p_240_29-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Clayson_p_240-29">[27]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-41"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-41"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">Starr's previous solo albums, <I><A href="/wiki/Sentimental_Journey_(Ringo_Starr_album)" title="Sentimental Journey (Ringo Starr album)">Sentimental Journey</A></I> and <I><A href="/wiki/Beaucoups_of_Blues" title="Beaucoups of Blues">Beaucoups of Blues</A></I> (both 1970), had been forays focusing on <A href="/wiki/Pop_standards" class="mw-redirect" title="Pop standards">pre-rock era standards</A> and <A href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</A>, respectively.<SUP id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-39">[36]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-40">[37]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-63"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-63"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">Alternatively, the line-up of Starr, Harrison, Wright and Voormann was the same as that on "Back Off Boogaloo",<SUP id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-60">[56]</A></SUP> recorded at Apple<SUP id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-61">[57]</A></SUP> in September 1971.<SUP id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-62">[58]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-66"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-66"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">The catalog numbers were Apple 1865 and Apple R 5992 in the US and the UK, respectively.<SUP id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-65">[60]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
<LI id="cite_note-69"><SPAN class="mw-cite-backlink"><B><A href="#cite_ref-69"><SPAN class="cite-accessibility-label">Jump up </SPAN>^</A></B></SPAN> <SPAN class="reference-text">The BBC aired the clip once on the music show <I><A href="/wiki/Top_of_the_Pops" title="Top of the Pops">Top of the Pops</A></I>, which was the only screening it received anywhere in the world.<SUP id="cite_ref-Badman_p_108_67-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Badman_p_108-67">[61]</A></SUP></SPAN></LI>
</OL>
</DIV>

<P>The <B>Super Bowl 50 Halftime Show</B> took place on February 7, 2016, at <A href="/wiki/Levi%27s_Stadium" title="Levi's Stadium">Levi's Stadium</A> in <A href="/wiki/Santa_Clara,_California" title="Santa Clara, California">Santa Clara, California</A> as part of <A href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_50" title="Super Bowl 50">Super Bowl 50</A>. It was headlined by the British rock group <A href="/wiki/Coldplay" title="Coldplay">Coldplay</A><SUP id="cite_ref-SB50HalftimeShow_1-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-SB50HalftimeShow-1">[1]</A></SUP> with special guest performers <A href="/wiki/Beyonc%C3%A9" title="Beyoncé">Beyoncé</A> and <A href="/wiki/Bruno_Mars" title="Bruno Mars">Bruno Mars</A>, who previously had headlined the <A href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVII_halftime_show" title="Super Bowl XLVII halftime show">Super Bowl XLVII</A> and <A href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVIII_halftime_show" title="Super Bowl XLVIII halftime show">Super Bowl XLVIII</A> halftime shows, respectively.</P>

<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Background">Background</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Background">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tleft">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg/220px-Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg" width="220" height="123" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg/330px-Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg/440px-Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3648" data-file-height="2040" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Broncos_vs_49ers_preseason_game_at_Levi%27s_Stadium.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
<A href="/wiki/Levi%27s_Stadium" title="Levi's Stadium">Levi's Stadium</A>, location of <A href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_50" title="Super Bowl 50">Super Bowl 50</A> and the halftime show</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P><A href="/wiki/Coldplay" title="Coldplay">Coldplay</A>, <A href="/wiki/Rihanna" title="Rihanna">Rihanna</A>, and <A href="/wiki/Katy_Perry" title="Katy Perry">Katy Perry</A> were considered as potential acts for the <A href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLIX_halftime_show" title="Super Bowl XLIX halftime show">Super Bowl XLIX halftime show</A> in 2015.<SUP id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-2">[2]</A></SUP> Perry was soon confirmed as the headliner of the halftime show in October 2014. In late November, 2015, reports surfaced stating that multiple acts would perform during the halftime show. Coldplay was confirmed as the lead half time performer for Super Bowl 50 on December 3, 2015, one day before the release of their seventh studio album <I><A href="/wiki/A_Head_Full_of_Dreams" title="A Head Full of Dreams">A Head Full of Dreams</A></I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-SB50HalftimeShow_1-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-SB50HalftimeShow-1">[1]</A></SUP> It was confirmed that Beyoncé and Bruno Mars would join Coldplay as special guests.<SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP> <A href="/wiki/Chris_Martin" title="Chris Martin">Chris Martin</A> called Mars to ask him to perform with Coldplay; however, Mars declined the offer. Nevertheless, the singer of Coldplay invited Mars to his studio in Malibu where he was working.<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP> There, Martin revealed to Mars that he wanted for him to perform "Uptown Funk" with Beyonce. Despite this, Mars still didn't think it was a good idea and asked the former to talk to Beyonce to see what was her opinion on that. Martin videotaped him and Mars, while the former sang a song to Beyoncé so that she would come to do the Super Bowl with both of them.<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Rap-Up_5-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Rap-Up-5">[5]</A></SUP> Beyonce response was receptive to the idea.<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP></P>
<P>At that time, Mars and Beyoncé were both doing a diet and stressing out.<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP> One day before the performance they were "watching playback backstage", while Beyonce ate a bag of Cheetos.<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP> Mars asked her "That's what you're doing?", to which she replied "There's nothing more we can do these last two days. It's gonna be what it's gonna be. So I'm gonna enjoy this bag of Cheetos."<SUP id="cite_ref-RSJE_4-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-RSJE-4">[4]</A></SUP> Mars strongly believes that Beyoncé is "coming for you every single time. So you better bring your A-game every time."<SUP id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-6">[6]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Performance">Performance</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Performance">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>

Coldplay frontman <A href="/wiki/Chris_Martin" title="Chris Martin">Chris Martin</A> during the performance.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_(24648386539).jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg/220px-Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg/330px-Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg/440px-Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_%2824648386539%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="6000" data-file-height="4000" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show_(24648386539).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
Field during the halftime show. The audience participates in a <A href="/wiki/Card_stunt" title="Card stunt">card stunt</A></DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The show opened with <A href="/wiki/Chris_Martin" title="Chris Martin">Chris Martin</A> singing the opening chorus from "<A href="/wiki/Yellow_(Coldplay_song)" title="Yellow (Coldplay song)">Yellow</A>". He was then joined by the remaining band members of Coldplay to perform "<A href="/wiki/Viva_la_Vida" title="Viva la Vida">Viva la Vida</A>", "<A href="/wiki/Paradise_(Coldplay_song)" title="Paradise (Coldplay song)">Paradise</A>", and "<A href="/wiki/Adventure_of_a_Lifetime" title="Adventure of a Lifetime">Adventure of a Lifetime</A>" with the <A href="/wiki/El_Sistema" title="El Sistema">Youth Orchestra Los Angeles</A> conducted by <A href="/wiki/Gustavo_Dudamel" title="Gustavo Dudamel">Gustavo Dudamel</A> and the <A href="/wiki/University_of_California_Marching_Band" title="University of California Marching Band">University of California Marching Band</A>. Bruno Mars, <A href="/wiki/Mark_Ronson" title="Mark Ronson">Mark Ronson</A>, and a troupe of backing dancers (dressed in the style of <A href="/wiki/Michael_Jackson" title="Michael Jackson">Michael Jackson</A><SUP id="cite_ref-apreview_7-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-apreview-7">[7]</A></SUP>) then performed "<A href="/wiki/Uptown_Funk" title="Uptown Funk">Uptown Funk</A>". Beyoncé, also in a Jackson-inspired outfit and appearing with a set of backing dancers dressed as <A href="/wiki/Black_Panther_Party" title="Black Panther Party">Black Panthers</A>, then performed her new single "<A href="/wiki/Formation_(song)" title="Formation (song)">Formation</A>" in a mass choreographed dance number before joining Mars onstage for a verse of "Uptown Funk". Coldplay played a snippet of "<A href="/wiki/Clocks_(song)" title="Clocks (song)">Clocks</A>" during a video montage of past Super Bowl halftime and national anthem performances, including those by <A href="/wiki/Bruce_Springsteen" title="Bruce Springsteen">Bruce Springsteen</A>, <A href="/wiki/Missy_Elliott" title="Missy Elliott">Missy Elliott</A>, <A href="/wiki/Katy_Perry" title="Katy Perry">Katy Perry</A>, <A href="/wiki/The_Rolling_Stones" title="The Rolling Stones">The Rolling Stones</A>, <A href="/wiki/Paul_McCartney" title="Paul McCartney">Paul McCartney</A>, <A href="/wiki/Stevie_Wonder" title="Stevie Wonder">Stevie Wonder</A>, <A href="/wiki/Diana_Ross" title="Diana Ross">Diana Ross</A>, <A href="/wiki/James_Brown" title="James Brown">James Brown</A>, <A href="/wiki/Whitney_Houston" title="Whitney Houston">Whitney Houston</A>, <A href="/wiki/Michael_Jackson" title="Michael Jackson">Michael Jackson</A>, <A href="/wiki/The_Black_Eyed_Peas" title="The Black Eyed Peas">The Black Eyed Peas</A>, <A href="/wiki/U2" title="U2">U2</A>, <A href="/wiki/Prince_(musician)" title="Prince (musician)">Prince</A>, Beyoncé and Mars. The show concluded with the band performing "<A href="/wiki/Fix_You" title="Fix You">Fix You</A>" and "Up&Up" with Beyoncé, Mars and everyone taking part in the show. At the end of the performance, the audience participated in a card-stunt creating a rainbow and the phrase, "Believe in love", the closing lyrics to Coldplay's <I><A href="/wiki/A_Head_Full_of_Dreams" title="A Head Full of Dreams">A Head Full of Dreams</A></I>.</P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Critical_reception">Critical reception</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Critical reception">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg/220px-Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg/330px-Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg/440px-Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3985" data-file-height="2657" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
<A href="/wiki/Bruno_Mars" title="Bruno Mars">Bruno Mars</A> performed at the Super Bowl 50 halftime show and received positive reviews.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The performance received generally mixed review from critics, who complimented Beyoncé and Mars' part of the performance but were critical of Coldplay. Jon Caramanica of <I><A href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</A></I> stated that Coldplay "acted more as a stagehand than an actual performer" while Beyoncé's section of the performance was "the night's true event". Caramanica also noted that Beyoncé and Mars "outsang" Martin during the closing part of the performance.<SUP id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-8">[8]</A></SUP> Andrew Barker of <I><A href="/wiki/Variety_(magazine)" title="Variety (magazine)">Variety</A></I> similarly noted that "Coldplay seemed resigned to politely allowing themselves to be played right off their own stage" by the "far flashier" Mars and Beyoncé.<SUP id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-9">[9]</A></SUP> In a review for <A href="/wiki/Fox_Sports_(United_States)" title="Fox Sports (United States)">Fox Sports</A>, Chris Chase panned Coldplay's performance, calling it "inexplicable, indecipherable, and unnecessary" and a "musical snooze". Chase complimented Beyoncé's and Mars' appearances but described the performance as "boring".<SUP id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-10">[10]</A></SUP> Alex Needham of <I><A href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</A></I> gave the performance four stars, saying that "Queen Bey at the height of her powers effortlessly overwhelmed Coldplay's widescreen anthems in a show that seemed lightweight until she showed up".<SUP id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-11">[11]</A></SUP></P>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg/220px-Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg/330px-Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg/440px-Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3153" data-file-height="2102" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Beyonce_and_Bruno_Mars_Super_Bowl_50.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
<A href="/wiki/Beyonc%C3%A9" title="Beyoncé">Beyoncé</A>, seen here performing at the show, was both praised and castigated for her performance.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>Robert Bianco of <I><A href="/wiki/USA_Today" title="USA Today">USA Today</A></I> stated that Martin "seemed overwhelmed" by the size of the event, and that despite being a "personable and energetic performer", an "awful lot" of Martin's energy "went into jumping". Bianco praised Beyoncé's appearance and stated that she "stole the show".<SUP id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-12">[12]</A></SUP> Wendy Geller of <A href="/wiki/Yahoo!" title="Yahoo!">Yahoo!</A> also complimented Beyoncé's and Mars' appearances, but criticized the montage of previous halftime performances, describing it as "confusing rather than touching" and stating that the performance was "definitely a cold play".<SUP id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-13">[13]</A></SUP></P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Controversy">Controversy</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Controversy">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>Following the performance, Beyoncé was criticized for performing a song that they considered to be "anti-police" during the halftime show and for appearing to align herself with the <A href="/wiki/Black_Lives_Matter" title="Black Lives Matter">Black Lives Matter</A> movement. Former <A href="/wiki/Mayor_of_New_York_City" title="Mayor of New York City">New York City mayor</A> <A href="/wiki/Rudy_Giuliani" title="Rudy Giuliani">Rudy Giuliani</A> accused the performance of being anti-police and also criticized Beyoncé's use of <A href="/wiki/Black_Power" title="Black Power">Black Power</A> and <A href="/wiki/Black_Panther_Party" title="Black Panther Party">Black Panther Party</A> symbolism in her dance routine. "This is <A href="/wiki/American_football" title="American football">football</A>, not <A href="/wiki/Cinema_of_the_United_States" title="Cinema of the United States">Hollywood</A>, and I thought it was really outrageous that she used it as a platform to attack police officers who are the people who protect her and protect us, and keep us alive," he said.<SUP id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-14">[14]</A></SUP> The controversy caused a "#BoycottBeyonce" hashtag on <A href="/wiki/Twitter" title="Twitter">Twitter</A> and protesters announced plans for an "anti-Beyoncé" rally on the morning of February 16 outside of the NFL's headquarters in New York City, but no one showed up for such a rally.<SUP id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-15">[15]</A></SUP> <A href="/wiki/CNN" title="CNN">CNN</A> political commentator Sally Kohn stated that "too many police continue to show themselves to be far more interested in reactionary defensiveness and preserving the abusive status quo."<SUP id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-16">[16]</A></SUP> Black Lives Matter activist Melina Abdullah praised Beyoncé and other artists who "are willing to raise social consciousness and use their artistry to advance social justice."<SUP id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-17">[17]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-18">[18]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Commercial_reception">Commercial reception</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Super_Bowl_50_halftime_show&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Commercial reception">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>The halftime show became the fourth highest ever watched show in the United States, with total viewership of 115.5 million.<SUP id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-19">[19]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-20">[20]</A></SUP></P>

<P><B>Matthew MacKendree "Matt" Lanter</B> (born April 1, 1983) is an American actor, voice actor, and model. He gained fame by playing <A href="/wiki/List_of_90210_characters#Liam_Court" title="List of 90210 characters">Liam Court</A> in <A href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CW</A> hit <A href="/wiki/Teen_drama" title="Teen drama">teen drama</A> series <I><A href="/wiki/90210_(TV_series)" title="90210 (TV series)">90210</A></I>, a <A href="/wiki/Spin-off_(media)" title="Spin-off (media)">spin-off</A> of the 1990s Fox series <I><A href="/wiki/Beverly_Hills,_90210" title="Beverly Hills, 90210">Beverly Hills, 90210</A></I>. He also appeared in some major released films, such as <I><A href="/wiki/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_(film)" title="Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)">Star Wars: The Clone Wars</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Disaster_Movie" title="Disaster Movie">Disaster Movie</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/WarGames:_The_Dead_Code" title="WarGames: The Dead Code">WarGames: The Dead Code</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Sorority_Row" title="Sorority Row">Sorority Row</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Vampires_Suck" title="Vampires Suck">Vampires Suck</A></I> and <I><A href="/wiki/The_Roommate" title="The Roommate">The Roommate</A></I>. He is the voice of <A href="/wiki/Anakin_Skywalker" class="mw-redirect" title="Anakin Skywalker">Anakin Skywalker</A> in <I><A href="/wiki/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_(2008_TV_series)" title="Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)">Star Wars: The Clone Wars</A></I> and <I><A href="/wiki/Star_Wars_Rebels" title="Star Wars Rebels">Star Wars Rebels</A></I>. He stars as soldier Wyatt Logan, a time traveler, in <I><A href="/wiki/Timeless_(TV_series)" title="Timeless (TV series)">Timeless</A></I> on <A href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBC</A>.</P>
<P></P>
