<P></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Career">Career</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Matt_Lanter&action=edit&section=1&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro" title="Edit section: Career">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>In 2004, Lanter was a contestant on <A href="/wiki/Bravo_(US_TV_channel)" class="mw-redirect" title="Bravo (US TV channel)">Bravo</A>'s reality show <I><A href="/wiki/Manhunt_(2004_TV_series)" title="Manhunt (2004 TV series)">Manhunt: The Search for America's Most Gorgeous Male Model</A></I>. He did not win the competition. Within a few weeks of moving to <A href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angeles</A>, <A href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</A>, Lanter successfully auditioned for the role of Nick on the supernatural teen-drama <A href="/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company" title="Fox Broadcasting Company">Fox</A> series <I><A href="/wiki/Point_Pleasant_(TV_series)" title="Point Pleasant (TV series)">Point Pleasant</A></I>. He had a major recurring role throughout the first and only season of the series. He has since then appeared in television shows such as <I><A href="/wiki/Grey%27s_Anatomy" title="Grey's Anatomy">Grey's Anatomy</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/8_Simple_Rules" title="8 Simple Rules">8 Simple Rules</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Big_Love" title="Big Love">Big Love</A></I> and <I><A href="/wiki/Heroes_(TV_series)" title="Heroes (TV series)">Heroes</A></I>.</P>
<P>In April 2005, he signed on to become a series regular portraying the role of Horace Calloway on <A href="/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company" title="American Broadcasting Company">ABC</A>'s political drama series <I><A href="/wiki/Commander_in_Chief_(TV_series)" title="Commander in Chief (TV series)">Commander in Chief</A></I>, starring <A href="/wiki/Geena_Davis" title="Geena Davis">Geena Davis</A> and <A href="/wiki/Donald_Sutherland" title="Donald Sutherland">Donald Sutherland</A>. The series premiered on September 27, 2005, ran for one season and was cancelled on June 14, 2006.</P>
<P>In 2008, he took on the lead role as Zach Conroy in <I><A href="/wiki/The_Cutting_Edge:_Chasing_the_Dream" title="The Cutting Edge: Chasing the Dream">The Cutting Edge: Chasing the Dream</A></I>, with <A href="/wiki/Francia_Raisa" title="Francia Raisa">Francia Raisa</A>.</P>
<P>In February 2008, he was announced to portray the <A href="/wiki/Leading_actor" title="Leading actor">lead role</A> of Will, in <A href="/wiki/Lionsgate" title="Lionsgate">Lionsgate</A>'s Parody/Comedy film <I><A href="/wiki/Disaster_Movie" title="Disaster Movie">Disaster Movie</A></I>. The film is written and directed by directing and screenwriting duo <A href="/wiki/Jason_Friedberg_and_Aaron_Seltzer" title="Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer">Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer</A> who have previously worked on other Parody films such as <I><A href="/wiki/Meet_The_Spartans" class="mw-redirect" title="Meet The Spartans">Meet The Spartans</A></I> and <I><A href="/wiki/Epic_Movie" title="Epic Movie">Epic Movie</A></I>. The film spoofs recent disaster films such as <I><A href="/wiki/Cloverfield" title="Cloverfield">Cloverfield</A></I>. He stars with <A href="/wiki/Kim_Kardashian" title="Kim Kardashian">Kim Kardashian</A>, <A href="/wiki/Vanessa_Minnillo" class="mw-redirect" title="Vanessa Minnillo">Vanessa Minnillo</A> and <A href="/wiki/Carmen_Electra" title="Carmen Electra">Carmen Electra</A>. The film, which was released on August 29, 2008, was a critical failure. The film grossed over $34 million worldwide and received extremely negative reviews from critics, as well as six nominations at the <A href="/wiki/29th_Golden_Raspberry_Awards" title="29th Golden Raspberry Awards">29th Golden Raspberry Awards</A>.</P>
<P>In October 2008, he was announced to star in <A href="/wiki/Summit_Entertainment" title="Summit Entertainment">Summit Entertainment</A>'s remake of the cult 1983 slasher film <I><A href="/wiki/The_House_on_Sorority_Row" title="The House on Sorority Row">The House on Sorority Row</A></I>. The film stars <A href="/wiki/Briana_Evigan" title="Briana Evigan">Briana Evigan</A>, <A href="/wiki/Audrina_Patridge" title="Audrina Patridge">Audrina Patridge</A>, and <A href="/wiki/Rumer_Willis" title="Rumer Willis">Rumer Willis</A>. <I><A href="/wiki/Sorority_Row" title="Sorority Row">Sorority Row</A></I> was released on September 11, 2009 to negative reviews.</P>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Matt_Lanter_2.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Matt_Lanter_2.jpg/220px-Matt_Lanter_2.jpg" width="220" height="331" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Matt_Lanter_2.jpg/330px-Matt_Lanter_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Matt_Lanter_2.jpg/440px-Matt_Lanter_2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2050" data-file-height="3081" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Matt_Lanter_2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
Lanter at the <A href="/wiki/Star_Wars_Weekends" title="Star Wars Weekends"><I>Star Wars</I> Weekends</A> in June 2009</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>In 2009, he began a major recurring role on <A href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CW</A>'s <I><A href="/wiki/90210_(TV_series)" title="90210 (TV series)">90210</A></I> portraying the role of <A href="/wiki/Liam_Court" class="mw-redirect" title="Liam Court">Liam Court</A>. In September 2009, he was announced as a series regular for the second season. The series is a sequel to the 1990s teen drama series <I><A href="/wiki/Beverly_Hills,_90210" title="Beverly Hills, 90210">Beverly Hills, 90210</A></I>. In March 2010, he signed on for another parody project with Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer, <A href="/wiki/20th_Century_Fox" title="20th Century Fox">20th Century Fox</A>'s <I><A href="/wiki/Vampires_Suck" title="Vampires Suck">Vampires Suck</A></I>. He played Edward Sullen, a spoof of <A href="/wiki/Edward_Cullen" title="Edward Cullen">Edward Cullen</A> from the <A href="/wiki/Twilight_(novel_series)" title="Twilight (novel series)"><I>Twilight</I> saga</A>. The film was released on August 18, 2010.</P>
<P>In May 2009, it was announced he had signed on for the role of Jason Webber in <A href="/wiki/Screen_Gems" title="Screen Gems">Screen Gems</A>' <A href="/wiki/Horror_film" title="Horror film">horror film</A> <I><A href="/wiki/The_Roommate" title="The Roommate">The Roommate</A></I>. Starring with <A href="/wiki/Minka_Kelly" title="Minka Kelly">Minka Kelly</A> and <A href="/wiki/Leighton_Meester" title="Leighton Meester">Leighton Meester</A>, filming took place in 2009. The film originally was scheduled for an October 2010 release but was pushed forward to September 17, 2010. However, Screen Gems pushed it to February 4, 2011.</P>
<P>He has worked on two films <I><A href="/wiki/Liars_All" title="Liars All">Liars All</A></I> and <I>A Chance of Rain</I>.<SUP id="cite_ref-heatworld_1-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-heatworld-1">[1]</A></SUP> He also voices <A href="/wiki/Harry_Osborn" title="Harry Osborn">Harry Osborn</A>, <A href="/wiki/Flash_Thompson" title="Flash Thompson">Flash Thompson</A> and <A href="/wiki/Venom_(comics)" title="Venom (comics)">Venom</A> in the TV series <I><A href="/wiki/Ultimate_Spider-Man_(TV_series)" title="Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)">Ultimate Spider-Man</A></I>,<SUP id="cite_ref-heatworld_1-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-heatworld-1">[1]</A></SUP> which premiered on April 1, 2012. He has also signed on to voice the role of Sled in <I><A href="/wiki/Secret_of_the_Wings" title="Secret of the Wings">Secret of the Wings</A></I>, which will be released in October 2012.</P>
<P>On March 5, 2013, Lanter was cast as a co-star in The CW's science fiction drama series <I><A href="/wiki/Star-Crossed_(TV_series)" title="Star-Crossed (TV series)">Star-Crossed</A></I> (originally titled <I>Oxygen</I>) opposite <A href="/wiki/Aimee_Teegarden" title="Aimee Teegarden">Aimee Teegarden</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-2">[2]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP> <I>Star-Crossed</I> is about a romance between a human girl (Teegarden) and an alien boy (Lanter) when he and six others of his kind are integrated into a suburban high school 10 years after they landed on Earth and were consigned to an internment camp.<SUP id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-4">[4]</A></SUP></P>
<P>In 2016, Lanter began playing the role of Wyatt Logan in the NBC series <I><A href="/wiki/Timeless_(TV_series)" title="Timeless (TV series)">Timeless</A></I> which is scheduled to broadcast a second season in early 2018.</P>
<H3><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Star_Wars"><I>Star Wars</I></SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Matt_Lanter&action=edit&section=2&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro" title="Edit section: Star Wars">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>
<P>In December 2006, he was announced to voice the role of <A href="/wiki/Darth_Vader" title="Darth Vader">Anakin Skywalker</A> for the animated film <I><A href="/wiki/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_(film)" title="Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)">Star Wars: The Clone Wars</A></I> which was released on August 15, 2008. The film had box office success earning worldwide $69,182,844. He continued in the role in the television series <I><A href="/wiki/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_(2008_TV_series)" title="Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)">Star Wars: The Clone Wars</A></I> which premiered on October 3, 2008 on the <A href="/wiki/Cartoon_Network" title="Cartoon Network">Cartoon Network</A>. He has also reprised his role in various video games based on the franchise. The series' fourth season premiered in September, 2011. Season five premiered on Cartoon Network on September 29, 2012. The Red Carpet Premier for the fifth Season was in Orlando, Florida during Celebration VI on Friday August 24, 2012 where Lanter along with some of his co-stars <A href="/wiki/Samuel_Witwer" class="mw-redirect" title="Samuel Witwer">Samuel Witwer</A>, <A href="/wiki/James_Arnold_Taylor" title="James Arnold Taylor">James Arnold Taylor</A>, <A href="/wiki/Dee_Bradley_Baker" title="Dee Bradley Baker">Dee Bradley Baker</A>, <A href="/wiki/Tom_Kane" title="Tom Kane">Tom Kane</A>, <A href="/wiki/Daniel_Logan" title="Daniel Logan">Daniel Logan</A> and <A href="/wiki/Stephen_Stanton" title="Stephen Stanton">Stephen Stanton</A> as well as Supervising Director <A href="/wiki/Dave_Filoni" title="Dave Filoni">Dave Filoni</A> attended this special event.</P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Personal_life">Personal life</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Matt_Lanter&action=edit&section=3&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro" title="Edit section: Personal life">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Lanter was born in <A href="/wiki/Massillon,_Ohio" title="Massillon, Ohio">Massillon, Ohio</A>, and moved to <A href="/wiki/Atlanta" title="Atlanta">Atlanta</A>, <A href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</A>, in 1991 at age eight.<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[5]</A></SUP> On June 14, 2013, he married his longtime girlfriend, Angela Stacy. The two had been in a relationship since 2009.<SUP id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-6">[6]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-7">[7]</A></SUP> They welcomed their first child, daughter MacKenlee Faire Lanter, on December 30, 2017.<SUP id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-8">[8]</A></SUP></P>

<P>"<B>A Whiter Shade of Pale</B>" is the debut single by the British rock band <A href="/wiki/Procol_Harum" title="Procol Harum">Procol Harum</A>, released 12 May 1967. The single reached number one in the <A href="/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart" title="UK Singles Chart">UK Singles Chart</A> on 8 June <A href="/wiki/1967_in_music" title="1967 in music">1967</A> and stayed there for six weeks.<SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP> Without much promotion, it reached number 5 on the <I>Bilboard</I> pop chart in the United States.<SUP id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-4">[4]</A></SUP> One of the anthems of the 1967 <A href="/wiki/Summer_of_Love" title="Summer of Love">Summer of Love</A>, it is one of fewer than 30 <A href="/wiki/Singles_(music)" class="mw-redirect" title="Singles (music)">singles</A> to have <A href="/wiki/List_of_best-selling_singles" title="List of best-selling singles">sold over 10 million</A> copies worldwide.<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[5]</A></SUP></P>
<P>With its <A href="/wiki/Bach" class="mw-redirect" title="Bach">Bach</A>-derived instrumental melody, soulful vocals, and unusual lyrics – by the song's co-authors <A href="/wiki/Gary_Brooker" title="Gary Brooker">Gary Brooker</A>, <A href="/wiki/Keith_Reid" title="Keith Reid">Keith Reid</A><SUP id="cite_ref-pc49_6-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-pc49-6">[6]</A></SUP> and <A href="/wiki/Matthew_Fisher" title="Matthew Fisher">Matthew Fisher</A> – "A Whiter Shade of Pale" reached No. 1 in several countries when released in 1967. In the years since, it has become an enduring classic. It was the most played song in the last 75 years in public places in the UK (as of 2009),<SUP id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-7">[7]</A></SUP> and the United Kingdom performing rights group <A href="/wiki/Phonographic_Performance_Limited" title="Phonographic Performance Limited">Phonographic Performance Limited</A> in 2004 recognised it as the most-played record by British broadcasting of the past 70 years.<SUP id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-8">[8]</A></SUP> Also in 2004, <I><A href="/wiki/Rolling_Stone" title="Rolling Stone">Rolling Stone</A></I> placed "A Whiter Shade of Pale" 57th on its list of the <A href="/wiki/List_of_Rolling_Stone%27s_500_Greatest_Songs_of_All_Time" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time">500 Greatest Songs of All Time</A>.</P>
<P>In 1977, the song was named joint winner (along with <A href="/wiki/Queen_(band)" title="Queen (band)">Queen</A>'s "<A href="/wiki/Bohemian_Rhapsody" title="Bohemian Rhapsody">Bohemian Rhapsody</A>") of "The Best British Pop Single 1952–1977" at the <A href="/wiki/Brit_Awards" title="Brit Awards">Brit Awards</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-9">[9]</A></SUP> In 1998 the song was inducted into the <A href="/wiki/Grammy_Hall_of_Fame" title="Grammy Hall of Fame">Grammy Hall of Fame</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-10">[10]</A></SUP> More than 1000 recorded cover versions by other artists are known.<SUP id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-11">[11]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-12">[12]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-13">[13]</A></SUP> The song has been included in many music compilations over the decades and has also been used in the soundtracks of numerous films, including <I><A href="/wiki/The_Big_Chill_(film)" title="The Big Chill (film)">The Big Chill</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Purple_Haze_(film)" title="Purple Haze (film)">Purple Haze</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Breaking_the_Waves" title="Breaking the Waves">Breaking the Waves</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/The_Boat_That_Rocked" title="The Boat That Rocked">The Boat That Rocked</A></I>, <A href="/wiki/Martin_Scorsese" title="Martin Scorsese">Martin Scorsese</A>'s segment of <I><A href="/wiki/New_York_Stories" title="New York Stories">New York Stories</A></I>, <I><A href="/wiki/Stonewall_(1995_film)" title="Stonewall (1995 film)">Stonewall</A></I>, and <A href="/wiki/Ken_Burns" title="Ken Burns">Ken Burns</A> and <A href="/wiki/Lynn_Novick" title="Lynn Novick">Lynn Novick</A>'s documentary series <I><A href="/wiki/The_Vietnam_War_(TV_series)" title="The Vietnam War (TV series)">The Vietnam War</A></I>. Cover versions of the song have also been featured in many films, for example, by <A href="/wiki/King_Curtis" title="King Curtis">King Curtis</A> in <I><A href="/wiki/Withnail_and_I" title="Withnail and I">Withnail and I</A></I> and by <A href="/wiki/Annie_Lennox" title="Annie Lennox">Annie Lennox</A> in <I><A href="/wiki/The_Net_(1995_film)" title="The Net (1995 film)">The Net</A></I>.</P>
<P>The original writing credits were for Brooker and Reid only. On 30 July 2009, Matthew Fisher won co-writing credit for the music in a unanimous ruling from the <A href="/wiki/Law_Lords" class="mw-redirect" title="Law Lords">Law Lords</A>.</P>
<P></P>

<P></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Recording_and_personnel">Recording and personnel</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Recording and personnel">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>The song was performed and recorded at <A href="/wiki/Olympic_Sound_Studios" class="mw-redirect" title="Olympic Sound Studios">Olympic Sound Studios</A> in <A href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</A>, England, with <A href="/wiki/Gary_Brooker" title="Gary Brooker">Gary Brooker</A> providing the vocals and piano, <A href="/wiki/Matthew_Fisher" title="Matthew Fisher">Matthew Fisher</A> on a <A href="/wiki/Hammond_Organ#M-100_series" class="mw-redirect" title="Hammond Organ">Hammond M-102</A> organ, <A href="/wiki/David_Knights" title="David Knights">David Knights</A> on bass and <A href="/wiki/Ray_Royer" class="mw-redirect" title="Ray Royer">Ray Royer</A> on guitar. Drums were by session drummer <A href="/wiki/Bill_Eyden" title="Bill Eyden">Bill Eyden</A>. A few days later, the song was re-recorded with the band's then newly recruited drummer <A href="/wiki/Bobby_Harrison" title="Bobby Harrison">Bobby Harrison</A>, but that version was discarded, and one of the original mono recordings was chosen for release.</P>
<P>Producer for the record was <A href="/wiki/Denny_Cordell" title="Denny Cordell">Denny Cordell</A>, and Keith Grant was the sound engineer.<SUP id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-14">[14]</A></SUP> The song was included on the US release of the <I><A href="/wiki/Procol_Harum_(album)" title="Procol Harum (album)">Procol Harum</A></I> album, in September 1967, but not on the later UK version.<SUP id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017191_15-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017191-15">[15]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Lyrics">Lyrics</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Lyrics">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Reid got the title and starting point for the song at a party. He overheard someone at the party saying to a woman, "You've turned a whiter shade of pale", and the phrase stuck in his mind.<SUP id="cite_ref-Simpson_16-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Simpson-16">[16]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-Johansen_17-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Johansen-17">[17]</A></SUP> The original lyrics had four verses, of which only two are heard on the original recording. The third verse has been heard in live performances by Procol Harum, and more seldom also the fourth.<SUP id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-18">[18]</A></SUP> The author of <I>Procol Harum: Beyond the Pale</I>, Claes Johansen, suggests that the song "deals in metaphorical form with a male/female relationship which after some negotiation ends in a sexual act".<SUP id="cite_ref-Johansen_17-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Johansen-17">[17]</A></SUP> This is supported by <A href="/wiki/Tim_de_Lisle" title="Tim de Lisle">Tim de Lisle</A> in <I>Lives of the Great Songs</I>, who remarks that the lyrics concern a drunken seduction, which is described through references to sex as a form of travel, usually nautical, using mythical and literary journeys.<SUP id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-19">[19]</A></SUP> Other observers have also commented that the lyrics concern a sexual relationship.<SUP id="cite_ref-Simpson_16-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Simpson-16">[16]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Contrary to the above interpretations, Reid was quoted in the February 2008 issue of <I><A href="/wiki/Uncut_(magazine)" title="Uncut (magazine)">Uncut</A></I> magazine as saying:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I was trying to conjure a mood as much as tell a straightforward, girl-leaves-boy story. With the ceiling flying away and room humming harder, I wanted to paint an image of a scene. I wasn’t trying to be mysterious with those images, I was trying to be evocative. I suppose it seems like a decadent scene I’m describing. But I was too young to have experienced any decadence, then. I might have been smoking when I conceived it, but not when I wrote. It was influenced by books, not drugs.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Structurally and thematically, the song is unusual in many respects. While the recorded version is 4:03 long, it is composed of only two verses, each with chorus. The piece is also more instrument-driven than most songs of the period, and with a much looser <A href="/wiki/Rhyme_scheme" title="Rhyme scheme">rhyme scheme</A>. Its unusually allusive and referential lyrics are much more complex than most lyrics of the time (for example, the chorus focuses on <A href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Chaucer" title="Geoffrey Chaucer">Chaucer</A>'s "<A href="/wiki/The_Miller%27s_Tale" title="The Miller's Tale">The Miller's Tale</A>"). Thus, this piece can be considered an early example of <A href="/wiki/Progressive_rock" title="Progressive rock">progressive rock</A>.<SUP class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<I><A href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><SPAN title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2017)">citation needed</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP></P>
<P>The phrase <I>a whiter shade of pale</I> has since gained widespread use in the English language, noticed by several dictionaries.<SUP id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-20">[20]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-21">[21]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-22">[22]</A></SUP> As such, the phrase is today often used in contexts independent of any consideration of the song.<SUP id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-23">[23]</A></SUP> It has also been heavily paraphrased, in forms like "an Xer shade of Y", to the extent that it has been recognised as a <A href="/wiki/Snowclone" title="Snowclone">snowclone</A><SUP id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-24">[24]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-25">[25]</A></SUP> – a type of <A href="/wiki/Clich%C3%A9" title="Cliché">cliché</A> and <A href="/wiki/Phrasal_template" title="Phrasal template">phrasal template</A>.</P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Composition">Composition</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Composition">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tright">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg/220px-Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg" width="220" height="145" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg/330px-Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg/440px-Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg 2x" data-file-width="450" data-file-height="297" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:Expo_Pink_Floyd_-_Organ.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
The song's distinctive, Bach-inspired organ part was played on a <A href="/wiki/Hammond_organ" title="Hammond organ">Hammond M102</A>.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The song is in moderate time in <A href="/wiki/C_major" title="C major">C major</A> and is characterised by the <A href="/wiki/Bassline" title="Bassline">bassline</A> moving stepwise downwards in a repeated pattern throughout. In classical music this is known as a <A href="/wiki/Ground_bass" class="mw-redirect" title="Ground bass">ground bass</A>. The harmonic structure is identical for the organ melody, the verse and the chorus, except that the chorus finishes with a <A href="/wiki/Cadence_(music)" title="Cadence (music)">cadence</A>. The main organ melody appears at the beginning and after each verse/chorus. But it is also heard throughout, playing variations of its theme and <A href="/wiki/Counterpoint" title="Counterpoint">counterpointing</A> the vocal line. As the chorus commences "And so it was, that later ...", the vocal and organ accompaniment begin a short <A href="/wiki/Crescendo" class="mw-redirect" title="Crescendo">crescendo</A>, with the organist running his finger rapidly down and up the entire keyboard. The final instrumental fades out to silence – a common device in pop music of the time.</P>
<P>Dutch author, and Bach aficionado, <A href="/wiki/Maarten_%27t_Hart" title="Maarten 't Hart">Maarten 't Hart</A> calls "A Whiter Shade of Pale" an "original adaptation" of <A href="/wiki/Johann_Sebastian_Bach" title="Johann Sebastian Bach">Johann Sebastian Bach</A>'s <A href="/wiki/Ich_steh_mit_einem_Fu%C3%9F_im_Grabe,_BWV_156" title="Ich steh mit einem Fuß im Grabe, BWV 156">Ich steh mit einem Fuß im Grabe, BWV 156</A>. Besides, the <A href="/wiki/Hammond_organ" title="Hammond organ">Hammond organ</A> line of the song came from Bach's "<A href="/wiki/Wachet_auf,_ruft_uns_die_Stimme,_BWV_140" title="Wachet auf, ruft uns die Stimme, BWV 140">Sleepers, Wake!</A>" and "<A href="/wiki/Air_on_the_G_String" title="Air on the G String">Air on the G String</A>", both of which use a similar stepwise bass motion. The similarity is referred to in the 1982 play <A href="/wiki/The_Real_Thing_(play)" title="The Real Thing (play)"><I>The Real Thing</I></A> by <A href="/wiki/Tom_Stoppard" title="Tom Stoppard">Tom Stoppard</A> and 1991 film <A href="/wiki/The_Commitments_(film)" title="The Commitments (film)"><I>The Commitments</I></A>. A yet closer melodic influence that is seldom cited can arguably<SUP class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<I><A href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><SPAN title="Who says this? (June 2010)">weasel words</SPAN></A></I>]</SUP> be found in the organ choral prelude "O Mensch bewein dein' Sünde groß" (O Man, Lament Your Sin So Great), <A href="/wiki/BWV" class="mw-redirect" title="BWV">BWV</A> 622, from Bach's <I><A href="/wiki/Orgelb%C3%BCchlein" title="Orgelbüchlein">Orgelbüchlein</A></I> (Little Organ Book). The music also borrows ideas from "<A href="/wiki/When_a_Man_Loves_a_Woman_(song)" title="When a Man Loves a Woman (song)">When a Man Loves a Woman</A>" by <A href="/wiki/Percy_Sledge" title="Percy Sledge">Percy Sledge</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-26">[26]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Release_and_reception">Release and reception</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Release and reception">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>The single was released on 12 May 1967 in the United Kingdom by <A href="/wiki/Deram_Records" title="Deram Records">Deram Records</A> and entered <I><A href="/wiki/Record_Retailer" title="Record Retailer">Record Retailer</A></I><SPAN class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</SPAN>s chart (later the <A href="/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart" title="UK Singles Chart">UK Singles Chart</A>) on 25 May. In two weeks it reached number 1, where it stayed for six weeks. Writing in 2005, Jim Irvin of <I><A href="/wiki/Mojo_(magazine)" title="Mojo (magazine)">Mojo</A></I> said that its arrival at number 1 on 8 June 1967, on the same day that <A href="/wiki/The_Beatles" title="The Beatles">the Beatles</A>' <I><A href="/wiki/Sgt._Pepper%27s_Lonely_Hearts_Club_Band" title="Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band">Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band</A></I> topped the national albums chart, marked the start of the <A href="/wiki/Summer_of_Love" title="Summer of Love">Summer of Love</A> in Britain.<SUP id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-27">[27]</A></SUP></P>
<P>According to music journalist and author Harvey Kubernik, in the context of the Summer of Love, "A Whiter Shade of Pale" was the "one song [that] stood above all others, its Everest-like status conferred by no less than <A href="/wiki/John_Lennon" title="John Lennon">John Lennon</A> and <A href="/wiki/Paul_McCartney" title="Paul McCartney">Paul McCartney</A>, who were enthralled by the Chaucerian wordplay and heavenly Baroque accompaniment".<SUP id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017191_15-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017191-15">[15]</A></SUP> Kubernik also writes that, amid the search for higher consciousness during the <A href="/wiki/Flower_power" title="Flower power">flower power</A> era, the song "galvanised a congregation of disaffected youth dismissive of traditional religion but anxious to achieve spiritual salvation".<SUP id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017149,_191_28-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKubernik2017149,_191-28">[28]</A></SUP></P>
<P>In the United States, the single reached number 5 on the <A href="/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100" title="Billboard Hot 100"><I>Billboard</I> Hot 100</A> and sold over 1 million copies. It also peaked at number 22 on the soul charts there.<SUP id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-29">[29]</A></SUP> In the Netherlands, the song entered the chart at number 1 in June 1967 and again reached number 1 in July 1972. A May 1972 re-release on <A href="/wiki/Fly_Records" title="Fly Records">Fly Records</A> stayed in the UK charts for a total of 12 weeks and peaked at number 13.</P>
<P>"A Whiter Shade of Pale" has continued to receive critical acclaim. Along with <A href="/wiki/Queen_(band)" title="Queen (band)">Queen</A>'s "<A href="/wiki/Bohemian_Rhapsody" title="Bohemian Rhapsody">Bohemian Rhapsody</A>", "A Whiter Shade of Pale" was jointly recognised as "The Best British Pop Single 1952–1977" at the <A href="/wiki/BRIT_Awards" class="mw-redirect" title="BRIT Awards">BRIT Awards</A>, part of <A href="/wiki/Elizabeth_II" title="Elizabeth II">Elizabeth II</A>'s <A href="/wiki/Silver_Jubilee" class="mw-redirect" title="Silver Jubilee">Silver Jubilee</A>. In 1998 the song was inducted into the <A href="/wiki/Grammy_Hall_of_Fame" title="Grammy Hall of Fame">Grammy Hall of Fame</A>. In 2004, it appeared at number 57 on <I><A href="/wiki/Rolling_Stone" title="Rolling Stone">Rolling Stone</A></I> magazine's list of the "<A href="/wiki/List_of_Rolling_Stone%27s_500_Greatest_Songs_of_All_Time" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time">500 Greatest Songs of All Time</A>". British TV station <A href="/wiki/Channel_4" title="Channel 4">Channel 4</A> placed the song at number 19 in its chart of "The 100 Greatest No. 1 Singles".<SUP id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-30">[30]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Promotional_films">Promotional films</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Promotional films">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tleft">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:192px;"><A href="/wiki/File:The_conservatory,_Witley_Court.jpg" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg/190px-The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg" width="190" height="143" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg/285px-The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg/380px-The_conservatory%2C_Witley_Court.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1536" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:The_conservatory,_Witley_Court.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
One of the clips for the song was filmed at <A href="/wiki/Witley_Court" title="Witley Court">Witley Court</A>, part of which was gutted by fire in 1937.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The first promotional clip for "A Whiter Shade of Pale" was shot in the ruins of <A href="/wiki/Witley_Court" title="Witley Court">Witley Court</A> in Worcestershire, England.<SUP id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-31">[31]</A></SUP> It features four of the five musicians who played on the hit single: Gary Brooker, Matthew Fisher, David Knights and Ray Royer, in performance and walking through the ruins. Only the drummer in the video isn't on the record: early band member Bobby Harrison is seen miming to session man Bill Eyden's drumming. The film was directed by <A href="/wiki/Peter_Clifton" title="Peter Clifton">Peter Clifton</A>, whose insertion of <A href="/wiki/Vietnam_War" title="Vietnam War">Vietnam War</A> newsreel footage caused it to be banned from airplay on the <A href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</A>'s <I><A href="/wiki/Top_of_the_Pops" title="Top of the Pops">Top of the Pops</A></I> TV show.<SUP id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-32">[32]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Procol Harum subsequently made a second promotional clip, using "<A href="/wiki/Scopitone" title="Scopitone">Scopitone</A>" technology. By this time, <A href="/wiki/Robin_Trower" title="Robin Trower">Robin Trower</A> and <A href="/wiki/B.J._Wilson" class="mw-redirect" title="B.J. Wilson">B.J. Wilson</A> had replaced Royer and Harrison in the band, so only three of the five musicians on the recording are represented. No performance footage appears in this film – only scenes of the five musicians cavorting around London and running across fields. The same lineup, with Fisher wearing a monk's <A href="/wiki/Cowl" title="Cowl">cowl</A>, mimed to the song on <I>Top of the Pops</I>, although Brooker sang live. Black-and-white footage of the performance has been shown online. The song represents 1967 in the 2004 release <I><A href="/wiki/Top_of_the_Pops_40th_Anniversary_1964%E2%80%932004_DVD" title="Top of the Pops 40th Anniversary 1964–2004 DVD">Top of the Pops 40th Anniversary 1964–2004 DVD</A></I>.</P>
<P>There was also a film shot as part of <A href="/wiki/Joel_Gallen" title="Joel Gallen">Joel Gallen</A>'s Deja-View music video series.<SUP id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-33">[33]</A></SUP> Originally airing on various networks in late 1985 through 1986, this video starred <A href="/wiki/Harry_Dean_Stanton" title="Harry Dean Stanton">Harry Dean Stanton</A> and <A href="/wiki/Bernie_Taupin" title="Bernie Taupin">Bernie Taupin</A>, but featured no member of the band. It has also aired on <A href="/wiki/VH1_Classic" class="mw-redirect" title="VH1 Classic">VH1 Classic</A>, and has recently surfaced online.<SUP id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-34">[34]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-35">[35]</A></SUP></P>
<DIV style="clear:both;"></DIV>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Authorship_lawsuit">Authorship lawsuit</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=A_Whiter_Shade_of_Pale&action=edit&section=6" title="Edit section: Authorship lawsuit">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>In 2005, former Procol Harum organist <A href="/wiki/Matthew_Fisher" title="Matthew Fisher">Matthew Fisher</A> filed suit in the <A href="/wiki/High_Court_of_Justice" title="High Court of Justice">High Court</A> against Gary Brooker and his publisher, claiming that he co-wrote the music for the song.<SUP id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-36">[36]</A></SUP> Fisher won the case on 20 December 2006 but was awarded 40% of the composers' share of the music copyright, rather than the 50% he was seeking and was not granted royalties for the period before 2005.<SUP id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-37">[37]</A></SUP></P>
<P>Brooker and publisher Onward Music were granted leave to appeal, and a hearing on the matter was held before a panel of three judges during the week of 1 October 2007. The decision, on 4 April 2008, by <A href="/wiki/Lord_Justice_Mummery" class="mw-redirect" title="Lord Justice Mummery">Lord Justice Mummery</A>, in the <A href="/wiki/Court_of_Appeal_of_England_and_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="Court of Appeal of England and Wales">Court of Appeal</A> upheld Fisher's co-authorship<SUP id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-38">[38]</A></SUP> but ruled that he should receive no royalties as he had taken too long (38 years) to bring his claim to litigation. Full royalty rights were returned to Brooker.<SUP id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-39">[39]</A></SUP></P>
<P>On 5 November 2008, Fisher was granted permission to appeal this decision to the <A href="/wiki/Judicial_functions_of_the_House_of_Lords" title="Judicial functions of the House of Lords">House of Lords</A>.<SUP id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-40">[40]</A></SUP> Lawyers say it is the first time the Law Lords have been asked to rule on a copyright dispute involving a song.<SUP id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-41">[41]</A></SUP> The appeal was heard in the House of Lords on 22–23 April 2009.<SUP id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-42">[42]</A></SUP></P>
<P>On 30 July 2009 the Law Lords unanimously ruled in Fisher's favour. They noted that the delay in bringing the case had not caused any harm to the other party; on the contrary he had benefited financially from it. They also pointed out that there were no time limits to copyright claims under English law. The right to future royalties was therefore returned to Fisher.<SUP id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-43">[43]</A></SUP><SUP id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-44">[44]</A></SUP> The musicological basis of the judgment, and its effect on the rights of musicians who contribute composition to future works, has drawn some attention in the music world.<SUP id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-45">[45]</A></SUP></P>
